<HEADLINE> NYSE Chairman Expresses Confidence in Chinese Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Richard Grasso, chairman and CEO
of the New York Stock Exchange, toured the Shanghai Stock Exchange
(SSE) today and commented on the leading role of Shanghai in
China's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Grasso, who is visiting China as guest of the Bank of China,
told reporters that he was deeply impressed by the SSE and amazed
at its great success over the past seven years. He noted the short
period required for the SSE to achieve a trading volume which
the NYSE reached after 70-odd years in operation.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese stock market is a developing one and
expressed his confidence in its bright future.
</P>
<P>
The eventual success of the Chinese stock market will play an
important role in China's economic development, said Grasso.
</P>
<P>
He added that rapid economic development in China will not only
benefit Chinese and overseas investors, but also be an important
factor in the overall success of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the NYSE will sponsor a consultants conference in
Beijing over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
SSE General Manager Tu Guangshao said the SSE now has 480
listed companies, including 379 A shares, 50 B shares and 34
securities. The total value for listed companies stands at 965.8
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Nine domestic companies and nine Chinese-funded companies
registered in Hong Kong and Singapore are listed on the NYSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
