<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Orders to Factories Decline in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Trade in U.S. aviation
products declined in February due to a slump in demand for
aircraft, the third time in the last five months, the Commerce
Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Orders for durable goods, items from appliances to airplanes
expected to last over three years, dipped 1.7 percent to a
seasonally adjusted 184 billion U.S. dollars, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
The monthly performance followed a 1.5 percent increase in
January, a partial recovery from a 5.3 percent plunge in December,
the worst showing in six years.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the drop reflects the fallout from
recessionary conditions in Asia, a big market for the U.S.
commercial airplanes.
</P>
<P>
In February, civilian aircraft orders plunged 34.2 percent,
more than offsetting a gain in automobile demand. Transportation
orders overall fell 8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
But manufacturing prospects look more positive. Orders rose 0.5
percent in February, the seventh increase in nine months.
</P>
<P>
Orders increased 3.2 percent for industrial machinery and 2.1
percent for primary metals such as steel. But orders for
electrical equipment fell 2.7 percent in the month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, shipments of durable goods, a measure of current
production, rose 2.2 percent last month. The combination of
falling orders and rising shipments reduced the backlog of
unfilled orders by 0.6 percent, the second decline in three
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
