<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karachi Stocks Up Amidst Thin Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Karachi shares index
appreciated Wednesday amidst thin trading as the city's main
commercial areas remained closed to observe a strike protesting
the deaths of 20 people in the city a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
Fighting between members of the Mutahida Qaumi Movement (MQM)
and its splinter group, the MQM (Haqiqi), has left 20 dead Tuesday
and both parties called for a strike Wednesday to protest the
killings.
</P>
<P>
The main shopping and commercial areas of the city remained
closed Wednesday in response to the strike call. This is the fifth
day of closure in the commercial district as Monday was a national
holiday following the weekend and Tuesday saw violence causing
businesses to remain shut.
</P>
<P>
Stocks market analysts say that trading volumes were low as the
city was not fully functional and the main commercial areas were
shut.
</P>
<P>
The 100-Index of Karachi Stock Exchange (KSE) went up 20.83
points to close at 1533.08 with a trading volume of 16 million
shares as compared to Tuesday's close of 1512.25 on 43 million
shares.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts were hopeful that the market would pick up in the
week as reaction to the city's violence was not as drastic as
market expectations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
