<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Acting Premier Against Cuts in Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 25 (Xinhua) - Russian Acting Prime Minister
Sergei Kiriyenko said Wednesday that Russia will not follow OPEC's
suggestion to cut daily oil production by 13,700 tons in effort to
boost prices.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with The Sevodnya newspaper, the former energy
minister stressed that production cutbacks would be dangerous for
Russia's oil infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
"Most oil wells in Russia are aged, and if they are temporarily
closed, 30 percent of them will never operate again," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government will be unable to compensate for
losses resulting from restrictions on oil production, he added.
</P>
<P>
Russia, which is the world's third largest oil producer, after
Saudi Arabia and the United States, suffered greatly from the
decrease in oil prices since early 1997.
</P>
<P>
OPEC will hold a special ministerial meeting on Monday in
Vienna to discuss the plan to cut output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
