<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Russian Economic Policy Will Not Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian economic policy will not
change because of the latest government reshuffle, a high-ranking
official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Yevgeny Grigoriyevich Yasin, acting minister without portfolio,
said that during the Soviet Union era and the initial stage of
Russian reform, it was true that the economic policy tended to
change with the governmental reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
But now every government is considering the economic and
financial issues and exercising caution in changing policy.
</P>
<P>
Yasin said, however, that he was more concerned with the
decling price of oil in the world market, possible floods in the
spring and the dramatic increase of delayed wages.
</P>
<P>
The Russian economic situation was not optimistic this year, he
said. Because of the price decline of oil in the world market,
Russia would lose nine billion U.S. dollars in the oil and oil
products markets.
</P>
<P>
According to the presidential decree, which dismissed the whole
government on Monday, previous government officials will continue
work until a new government is in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
