<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Accused for Cutting Humanitarian Aid in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, March 25 (Xinhua)-- The Joint Health Authority
(JHA) Wednesday accused the European Union (EU) for cutting
humanitarian assistance to the non-governmental organizations
(NGOs) in Somalia's Middle Shabelle region.
</P>
<P>
JHA said at a press conference here that EU, prompted by the
worsening security situation in Middle Shabelle Region, has
decided to cut humanitarian assistance to the NGOs operating in
the region effective on March 31.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Osman Mohamud Dufle, the JHA
coordinator, characterized the EU decision as "an inhumane act"
which is punishing the people of Middle Shabelle region
collectively.
</P>
<P>
"Insecurity is a general issue caused by the lack of a central
government for Somalia," said Dufle.
</P>
<P>
The health authority was especially troubled by the fading
hope for thousands of tuberculosis patients who now are only
undergoing the first stages of their treatment.
</P>
<P>
Once treatment is interrupted for a period, the doctors said,
the disease will resist any further treatments.
</P>
<P>
Dufle also said that the EU decision coincided with an
alarming epidemic measles disease which mainly affects children
under five.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics distributed to reporters, more than
180 cases of measles were recorded in the Capital alone in the
past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The health authority has appealed to the United Nations
agencies and the Somali aid coordination body to take measures to
help stop the spread of the measles disease and rescue those
already affected in Galdudud, Middle Shabelle, Benadir and Lower
Shablle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
