<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scholars Deepening Understanding with Realistic Attitude </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Two noted Harvard Sinologists
today attributed recent improvements in ties between China and the
United States to the "realistic" attitude adopted by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Professors Erza Vogel and William Kirby, China specialists who
frequently visit China, accompanied Harvard University President
Neil Rudenstine on the most recent trip to attend centennial
celebrations at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
The two scholars used today's briefing as a forum to call for
expanded contacts in wide-ranging areas to resolve common
problems arising in the increasingly interdependent world.
</P>
<P>
Vogel, director of both the Harvard University Asia Center and
prestigious Fairbank Center for East Asia Research, teaches a core
curriculum on "Industrial East Asia" and recently edited the book
"Living with China." Vogel has previously expounded his views
concerning the so-called "China Threat" in an article carrying the
headline "Must We Make China an Enemy?".
</P>
<P>
Vogel, the second director of the Fairbank Center, said the
American media has neglected ongoing profound changes taking place
in China, including the "growth of rural elections, the spread of
rule by law and the adaptation of international institutions."
</P>
<P>
"The voice of extreme is not always the mainstream," said
Vogel, adding that "distinguishing mainstream from sidestream
demands high level of knowledge of the United States."
</P>
<P>
Kirby, who currently chairs Harvard's Department of History and
Council on East Asian Studies, said the "greatest 20th century
threat to world peace is to weak China and divide China, turning
it play thing under the global powers."
</P>
<P>
The historian noted that "natural development" enabled China to
become stronger in the 20th century and follow its historic role
as one of the great civilizations. "A stronger, ever more
prosperous China is critically in interest of the world," said
Kirby. He pointed to the divergence between the two countries and
called for China and the United States "to look at things we have
in common and how we can solve those problems with the realization
that not all problems can be solved right away."
</P>
<P>
Kirby said he is currently working on three books related to
China -- "The International Development of China," "China and the
World in 20th Century," and "A World Transformed: A Global History
of the 20th Century." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
