<HEADLINE> U.S. Existing Home Sales Shoot up in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. existing home sales
soared 8.7 percent to a new record in February, the National
Association of Realtors said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The low mortgage rates helped boost sales of existing homes to
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 4.75 million units in
February, the highest since the association began tracking sales
in 1968.
</P>
<P>
The strong resales posed a sharp contrast with some economists'
earlier prediction of a relatively modest increase of 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
By region, sales went up 10.7 percent in the South to an annual
rate of 1.86 million units, 8.3 percent in the Midwest to 1.18
million, 7.4 percent in the West to 1.02 million, and 4.6 percent
in the Northeast to 680,000.
</P>
<P>
The nation-wide median price of an existing home was 124,300
U.S. dollars, up 5.8 percent from a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
