<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Clinton to Face Opposition in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Liu Yegang)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 25 (Xinhua) -- The state visit by U.S.
President Bill Clinton to South Africa has come under fire from
groups which plan to hold protests during the four-day tour.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will touch down in Cape Town early on Thursday on the
only state visit of his six-nation African tour, the longest of
his presidency to date.
</P>
<P>
The Friends of Cuba Society of South Africa condemned the U.S.
for its "hypocrisy" in supporting Africa's economic recovery
while it continued its immoral and inhumane blockade of food and
medication to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The South African public should be aware of the incredible
hardships that Clinton continues to impose on the people of Cuba,
the society said in a statement issued here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The society described the U.S. economic blockade of Cuba as
illegal and called on the Clinton administration to lift it.
</P>
<P>
"As Africans, we reconfirm that the economic upliftment of
Cuba and Africa is integrally linked. One cannot therefore extend
a hand of friendship to Africa while not at the same time
extending it to Cuba," the society said.
</P>
<P>
The head of the South African National Protection Service,
Andre Kruse, said Wednesday that a few groups planning to disrupt
Clinton's visit were being monitored.
</P>
<P>
Western Cape provincial head for national security service,
Flip Nel, said that a Muslim organisation in Cape Town had
applied for permission to hold a poster-placard demonstration
during Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
The group wants to demonstrate "global oppression" during
Clinton's address to the national parliament on Friday, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
The South African Campaign Against Landmines Wednesday called
on the U.S. government to sign a treaty banning landmines.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, the organisation said it is ironic
that the American leader is visiting Africa to discuss economic
recovery support.
</P>
<P>
It said that one of the most critical impending recovery on
the continent is the millions of hectares of land that cannot be
developed as a result of millions of explosive devices.
</P>
<P>
Africa is a continent solidly behind a treaty prohibiting
production, stockpiling, transfer and use of anti-personnel
mines, said the group.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-eight African countries, including the 14 members of
the Southern African Development Community (SADC), have signed
the treaty.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. government refused to approve it, the group noted
in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The South African lobby group said that while Clinton travels
through Africa, it is collecting signatures protesting against
U.S. policy on the explosive devices.
</P>
<P>
The visit is also likely to be criticized by the public and
citizens who will find travel difficult while the 1000-strong
entourage is in Cape Town and Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
But Ministry for Foreign Affairs Director for the Americans,
Dumisani Khumalo, called for calm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
