<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haikou Ranks First in Air Quality Among China's Major Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Haikou, capital of south China's
Hainan Province, ranked first in air quality among more than 30
major Chinese cities, according to the latest test conducted by
China's Environment Monitoring Center.
</P>
<P>
Since June of 1997, the center has been conducting weekly tests
in the country's municipalities, provincial capitals, special
economic zones and coastal scenic cities. The results have been
disclosed by announcing air pollution indexes.
</P>
<P>
The latest test shows that Haikou's index averages 28 with a
maximum of 30. The state-set index for a first-class city is below
50.
</P>
<P>
Observers attribute the result to the fact that the city never
seeks interim economic profit at the expense of the environment and
refuses to allow projects that would be heavy polluters.
</P>
<P>
To reduce tail-pipe emissions, the city has banned diesel
vehicles from the city proper and, beginning April 1, will promote
the use of lead-free gasoline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
