<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LDP Okeys Gung-ho Economic Stimulus Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP) has approved a 16 trillion yen (123.1 billion
U.S. dollar) package to stimulate the sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
The country's largest-ever economic stimulus package was
endorsed at an extraordinary meeting of the LDP General Council,
the ruling party's highest decision-making panel.
</P>
<P>
The party will submit the policy proposals to the government
after seeking endorsement from its two non-cabinet parliamentary
allies -- the Social Democratic Party and the New Party Sakigake.
</P>
<P>
The package includes bringing forward deadlines to finish
public works contracts, collectively worth 80.1 percent of the
public works appropriation in the 1998 fiscal budget.
</P>
<P>
Public works projects account for the majority of the package,
which also features tax breaks relating to education and welfare
fields, council members said.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to information and telecommunications
infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
The plan proposes using part of Japan's pool of postal savings
and postal insurance premiums to buoy the stock market.
</P>
<P>
But the LDP stopped short of including much-touted plans to cut
individual and corporate income taxes in the stimulus package.
</P>
<P>
Japanese opposition parties criticized the package as
inappropriate and renewed their calls for big income and corporate
tax cuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
