<HEADLINE> Yemen, U.N. Population Fund Sign Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Yemen and the U.N. Population Fund
signed an agreement here Thursday on training midwives to cut the
mortality rates of mothers and infants in the country, the Yemeni
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Holland government would provide 5.5
million U.S. dollars for the training of 1,500 midwives in the
country by the year 2001, and the Yemeni government, 390.5 million
rials (2.95 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The country's mother and child care projects were expected to
be improved with the implementation of birth control methods aimed
at reducing fertility rate, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Yemeni Minister of Planning and
Development Abdul Qader ba Jammal and Health Minister Abdullah
Abdul-Wali Nasher, and the fund's resident representative in
Sanaa Som Boasini. 
</P>
