<HEADLINE> New Measure Governs Inland Residents' Travel to Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- A new measure governing inland
residents' travel to Hong Kong for non-official purposes will be
implemented on March 30, an official with the Ministry of Public
Security announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Passports will no longer be issued by exit and entry
administration departments under the public security organs in the
country for inland residents to visit Hong Kong, the official
said. Instead, the departments will issue passes for travel to
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
These departments will approve applications according to
related regulations and then issue the passes for those allowed to
go to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A quota will be introduced for inland residents traveling to
Hong Kong for commercial purposes, said the official, and priority
will be given to business people and technicians participating in
large-scale and profitable enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The official said the new measure will apply to Chinese
employees of representative offices of international organizations
in China; Chinese working for foreign consulates, embassies and
press organizations stationed in China; and inland residents
engaged in foreign-funded, collective-owned and private
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Permits which were issued by the Hong Kong Immigration
Department and visas which were issued by the British Hong Kong
authorities will continue to be valid. Inland residents can go to
Hong Kong with passports and certificates until the documents'
expiration, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Passes which were issued by exit and entry administration
departments in inland areas for travel to Hong Kong and Macao can
also be used until they expire, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
