<HEADLINE> China's First Seedling Plant in Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 26 (Xinhua) -- China's first seedling plant,
affiliated with a Shanghai horticulturial farm, began operation on
a trial basis today, signaling Chinese farmers' liberation from
the tedious work of sowing and looking after young plants.
</P>
<P>
With a planned investment of 6.2 million yuan (747,000 U.S.
dollars), the 3,300-square-meter plant is composed of a
sowing workshop, a seedling catalysis room and a greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
Crop seeds can be sown on the production line and supplied with
enough heat and light through an automatic monitoring system. The
survival rate of seedlings exceeds 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
The facility is now producing seedlings of 13 vegetable
varieties. It is expected to turn out 10 million seedlings each
year with an annual output value of 5.8 million yuan when it goes
into full operation in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
