<HEADLINE> U.S. Diplomat Discusses Security Issues, Clinton Visit to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S.-China discussions on arms
control, nonproliferation and international security are "very
productive" issues, said John Holum, U.S. Acting Under Secretary
of State for Arms Control and International Security Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Holum, also director of the U.S. Arms Control and Disarmament
Agency, made the remarks at a press conference here today at the
U.S. embassy in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"In October 1997, President Bill Clinton and President Jiang
Zemin agreed to deepen the dialogue on security issues between the
United States and China," Holum said.
</P>
<P>
To advance this effort, he added, "we held two days of very
productive discussions with China's Vice-Foreign Minister Zhang
Deguang on the full range of arms control, nonproliferation and
international security issues."
</P>
<P>
After arriving in Beijing Wednesday, Holum also met with
China's new Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, Vice-Foreign Minister
Yang Jiechi, and Xiong Guangkai, deputy chief of the General Staff
of the Chinese People's Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
"In our meetings," Holum said, "we agreed to increase and
intensify our discussions in the security area in anticipation of
the visit by President Clinton to China in June. I expect to meet
with Vice-Foreign Minister Zhang again in the near future to
continue our consultations and to help prepare for the upcoming
meeting between our presidents."
</P>
<P>
In particular, Holum said, "we consulted on our common efforts
to promote peace and stability in Asia, to advance international
arms control and to prevent the proliferation of weapons of mass
destruction and missiles."
</P>
<P>
Mentioning some areas of interest, he said, "we discussed
implementation of the Peaceful Nuclear Cooperation Agreement and
ways of expanding our mutual efforts to prevent the spread of
missiles and chemical weapons. We also exchanged views on the
possibility of peaceful space cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed on the importance of strengthening the Biological
Weapons Convention to help address the threat posed by the
proliferation of biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
"We exchanged views on recent developments concerning the
Korean Peninsula, including our common efforts to advance the Four
Party Peace Talks process."
</P>
<P>
Holum also expressed his thanks to the Chinese delegation to
the discussions for their "hard work, constructive efforts and
hospitality."
</P>
<P>
Holum arrived in Beijing Wednesday for another series of
regular sub-cabinet level discussions, and his current trip is
part of preparations for Clinton's June visit to China.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to leave Beijing Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
