<HEADLINE> Long March Rocket's Success Rate Reaches World Advanced Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese Long March 2C rocket
smoothly sent two U.S.-made satellites into orbit at the Taiyuan
Satellite Launch Center early this morning.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese space expert said here today that the success rate of
China's rocket launches is approaching advanced international
levels.
</P>
<P>
Since 1970 when it began to use the Long March Carrier Rocket
to propel satellites into the skies, China has launched 50 rockets
with 44 successes and six failures, an 88 percent success rate.
</P>
<P>
The Long March rockets have put 50 satellites in preset space
orbits, including 17 commercial satellites for the United States,
Sweden, Australia, Pakistan, the Philippines and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The space expert said that the success rate of the Long March
Rockets' 50 flights has approached or exceeded that of the first
50 rocket launches by advanced countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that with the continual growth of China's comprehensive
national strength, the number of Long March Rocket yearly launches
will increase.
</P>
<P>
China will also continue to increase its investment in the
development of space technology, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
