<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workers' Representatives Congress Has a Say in Lay-offs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Enterprises must make
explanations to the Worker's Representative Congress before they
announce a list of laid-off workers, said Beijing Mayor Jia
Qinglin here today.
</P>
<P>
"While strictly adhering to the state's policies on lay-offs,
enterprises have to work out settlement plans for the laid-off
workers," said Jia Qinglin, also member of the Political Bureau
of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China, at the
first plenary meeting of the new municipal government.
</P>
<P>
"The municipal government will give priority to the
re-employment of laid-off workers this year," said Jia.
</P>
<P>
The city must provide job opportunities for over 400,000 people
in 1998, according to him. Among them are 32,900 jobless, 190,000
laid-off workers and a new work force of 200,000.
</P>
<P>
Although the phenomenon of lay-offs is beneficial to economic
growth by raising efficiency, Jia said, governments at all levels
should make an effort to ensure the basic living standard of the
laid-offs and to create more job opportunities for them.
</P>
<P>
The mayor urged government departments concerned to offer
assistance to laid-off workers willing to be self-employed or run
collective enterprises. He also urged the departments to organize
training programs for them.
</P>
<P>
Jia said that by 2,000 the municipal government should ensure
that more than 90 percent of the laid-off workers who are willing
to be re-employed will be registered at the re-employment service
center. More than 80 percent of them should be provided with jobs,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
