<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Huge Export Financing Loan for Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
approved Thursday its participation in a one-billion-US-dollar
export financing facility for Thailand in order to provide
badly-needed credit for Thai exporters.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, the Manila-based ADB said the facility will
provide liquidity for Thai exporters whose operations have been
severely hampered by lack of credit and help Thailand recover from
the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The facility consists of two loans to the Export-Import Bank of
Thailand -- a 50-million-dollar loan from the ADB and a
950-million-dollar syndicated loan fully underwritten by ten
leading international banks.
</P>
<P>
Each loan has a maturity of five years. For the syndicated
loan, the ADB has agreed to guarantee principal repayments and
interest payments due in the first three years.
</P>
<P>
This is the first major term financing for Thailand since it
was hit by the financial crisis last year and is the ADB's first
export-financing loan.
</P>
<P>
"This is a significant milestone as it signals the return of
Thailand to the international bank loan market and recognition
that the recovery of Thailand is well under way," ADB president
Mitsuo Sato was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Given the sharp depreciation of the Thai baht since last year,
Thai exports are projected to grow sharply, provided there are no
financing constraints, the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
However, at present, commercial banks in Thailand are facing
extreme liquidity problems. Export-related funding requirements in
Thailand from 1998 to 2000 are estimated at 160 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karachi Stocks Jump by 35.54 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The 100-Index of Karachi Stock
Exchange (KSE) was up Thursday by 35.54 points to close at 1568.62
as against Wednesday's closing of 1533.08 points.
</P>
<P>
