<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are some major
news items in leading U. S. newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton, speaking in Rwanda, called for
sharper vigilance against genocide and swifter prosecution of its
perpetrators in a new permanent international criminal court.
Clinton acknowledged that the world could have protected the
victims of Rwanda's 1994 genocide, but did not. After listening
to several victims' accounts, Clinton said that "we cannot change
the past," but that nations should learn from it.
</P>
<P>
-- The United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan said in a
speech to the Israel Council on Foreign Relations that he was
delivering "the most difficult message" of his visit to Israel:
his accusation that Israel had committed a chain of "provocative
acts" that had contributed to a crisis in Israeli-Arab relations.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Convinced that flagging Israeli-Palestinian talks are near
collapse and already doing substantial harm to U.S. rgional
interests, President Clinton has decided in principle to unveil an
American peacemaking package that the Israeli government
categorically rejects, according to senior policymakers.
</P>
<P>
-- Indonesian officials say they expect to be able to unveil as
early as next week a new and improved economic reform package --
the third in the country in less than five months. They hope the
plan will not only stabilize the volatile currency but also revive
the ailing banking sector and tackle massive private-sector debt.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The IMF-funding debate became more contentious as U.S.
Senate Republican leaders warned colleagues not to play games with
the issue amid the Asian financial crisis. An angry address by
Appropriations Chairman Stevens appeared aimed at conservatives
who have delayed the 18 billion U.S. dollars measure. A vote is
due Thursday.
</P>
<P>
-- New sanctions on Serbia were rejected by U.S. allies for
now, despite Washington's warnings that Belgrade continues to
repress ethnic Albanians in Kosovo province. Russia agreed to
allow a U.N. vote on an arms embargo this month, but a decision on
freezing overseas assets was postponed for at least four weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
