<HEADLINE> China's Defense Minister Meets Japanese Guests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Chi Haotian, vice-chairman of
China's Central Military Commission and defense minister, met here
today with Fujinawa Yuji, chief of staff of the Japanese Ground
Self-Defense Forces.
</P>
<P>
Chi, who is also a state councillor, extended a welcome to
Fujinawa and said the current generations should not forget the
painstaking efforts that the older generations of Chinese and
Japanese had made to promote friendly relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the 20th anniversary of the signing of the
Sino-Japanese Treaty of Peace and Friendship, he said he hopes the
two nations will use the opportunity to further bilateral
relations in political, economic, cultural, military and other
areas.
</P>
<P>
He said relations between defense departments of the two
countries and the Chinese People's Liberations Army (PLA) and the
Japanese Self-Defense Forces have developed and exchanges of
high-level visits have taken place, both of which demonstrate
Sino-Japanese relations have entered a new stage.
</P>
<P>
"Past experience, if not forgotten, is a guide for the future,"
China's defense minister said, adding that Chinese leaders have
always emphasized that the Japanese should draw lessons from
history to avoid repeating past mistakes.
</P>
<P>
"We are duty-bound to advance friendly relations between our
two neighbors," Chi said.
</P>
<P>
Fujinawa said the Japanese will have a correct understanding
of and conduct deep self-examination on the questions rooted in
history and contribute to building friendly Japan-China relations
geared to the future.
</P>
<P>
Fujinawa said he feels glad to visit China as the first officer
of his post, and that increases in bilateral military exchanges
will help further friendly relations between the two countries and
their defense departments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
