<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 SLA Members Seek Political Asylum in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Four members of the South
Lebanese Army (SLA) have entered into Israel and sought political
asylum in the country, the Israel army said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The four, one officer and three soldiers, are from one family
and they have asked Israel to allow them to stay and grant
citizenship to them and all their family members.
</P>
<P>
The SLA has been assisting Israeli occupation forces in
fighting resistance Muslim guerrillas and is regarded as traitors
by Lebanese people.
</P>
<P>
The four, whose names were not disclosed, said their future
remains uncertain after Israel pulls out its troops from South
Lebanon and nobody could guarantee their safety and that of their
family members.
</P>
<P>
Israel has said it is willing to comply with U.S. Security
Council resolution 425 and withdraw from Lebanon provided that
arrangements are made to ensure the security of northern Israel
and the safety of the SLA forces.
</P>
<P>
The proposal has been rejected by Lebanon, which demanded an
unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon, as stipulated
by the resolution 425 adopted by the Security Council in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and set up a
1,100-square-kilometer security zone in the south in 1985, where
it is engaged in an attrition war with resistance guerrillas,
especially the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
Israeli government has promised to make its final decision on
this issue very soon and also asked the U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan, who just ended a three-day visit here, to help solve
this problem.
</P>
<P>
SLA Commander Gen. Antoine Lahad, who has been condemned by a
Lebanese court to death for treason in absentia, visited Israel
last week to discuss the Israeli pullout and future of his SLA
forces.
</P>
<P>
He asked Israel not to exit unilaterally as proposed by
National infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, the very former
general who then masterminded the establishment of security zone,
before security arrangements are made with parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
Lahad also worried his SLA's future and some reports said that
Lahad and other senior SLA officers would be granted political
asylum in France after Israeli withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
