<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
Riyadh -- A new oilfield in the eastern part of the Saudi
Arabia with a capacity of pumping 500,000 barrels will come into
operation by the middle of this year, according to Saudi Minister
of Petroleum and Minerals.
</P>
<P>
Ali Al-Nouaimi said his country would pursue efforts to develop
national oil industry and exploit all available resources for the
purpose.
</P>
<P>
Oil reserves of Saudi Arabia, the world top oil producer and
exporter, are estimated at 261 billion barrels, accounting to 32.8
percent of the reserves of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries and 25.6 percent of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
Jedda -- The Gulf Company, one of the biggest Saudi companies
specializing in electronic network projects, will set up the
first Gulf data network due to come into operation completely by
the end of the current year, 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to Saleh El-Alehaidan, vice chairman of the Eastern
Region Chamber of Commerce and Industry, the multi-million
U.S. dollar Gulf Data Network project is to be sponsored by
chambers of commerce of the Gulf Cooperation Council states with
the aim of facilitate communications among them.
</P>
<P>
Sanaa -- Yemen's tourism revenues in 1997 amounted to 70
million U.S. dollars, 29 million dollars more than the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Qafla, deputy director of Yemen's General Tourism
Authority, said that Yemen received last year 80,000 tourists,
most of them from Italy, Germany, France and the Netherlands, and
is expected to received some 100,000 tourists this year.
</P>
<P>
Abu Dhabi -- The current chairman of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, Obeid bin Saif al-Nasir affirmed
that the organization would hold an emergency meeting next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Reliable OPEC sources revealed that a number of non-OPEC
members would be invited to attend this meeting. Al-Nasir, who is
the United Arab Emirates oil minister, said the meeting would
adopt an accord signed in Saudi capital Riyadh on Sunday and make
it legally binding.
</P>
<P>
The accord, signed by oil ministers of Saudi Arabia, Venezuela
and Mexico, provides for an oil output cut of between 1.6 million
and 2 million barrels per day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
