<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Quarter Jordanians Live in Poverty: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 26 (Xinhua) -- One million Jordanians, or 26
percent of the whole population, are living in absolute poverty,
semi-official Jordan Times Thursday quoted Minister of Social
Development Mohammed Mamsir as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister did not specify what the absolute poverty is, but
he further said that by the end of 1997, about 45 percent of the
families in the kingdom are leading a hard life with less than 150
Jordanian dinars (about 212 U.S. dollars) monthly income, an
amount that could barely support the family members with enough
daily bread.
</P>
<P>
Most alarming, illiteracy and malnutrition, by-products of
poverty, are increasing too, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Independent agencies have estimated that over 20 percent of
Jordanian children under 12 suffer from malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
The roots of poverty in Jordan, a country with few natural
resources, are diverse, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom is burdened with huge foreign debts which was
estimated at 4.7 billion dinars (6.6 billion dollars) in 1997
while suffering from an awesome annual population growth rate of
3.4 percent, which is among the world's highest.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the country, with up to 25 percent of its
labor force unemployed, according to independent estimates, had an
influx of about 300,000 returning Jordanians during the 1990-91
Gulf Crisis.
</P>
<P>
These Jordanian workers were expelled by some Arab Gulf countries
during the crisis, triggered by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, because
Jordan sided with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In efforts to combat poverty, the government and the private
sector spent 140 million dinars (about 198 million dollars) last
year to help the poor in various ways, Mamsir said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the state-run National Aid Fund, said it is looking
into plans to raise the ceiling of monthly handouts for every
family to over 60 dinars (85 dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, local observers say that the government appears to
lack a comprehensive strategy to help ease the growing poverty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
