<HEADLINE> Beijing Builds 67 Projects for China's 50th Birthday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Beijing has started building 67 giant
projects with an investment of 116 billion yuan (14 billion
U.S. dollars) to mark the 50th birthday of the People's Republic
of China, Vice-Mayor Wang Guangtao said here today.
</P>
<P>
The 67 projects, scheduled to be completed before
October of 1999, will showcase the features of Beijing as well as
the country's highest modern design and building standards for
architecture, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The completion of all the projects -- including 16
infrastructure buildings, 37 public utilities and 14 housing
structures -- will give the municipality a new appearance and help
stimulate the growth of the local economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
Workers are expediting the subway expansion project from
downtown Fuxingmen to eastern Bawangfen.
</P>
<P>
Other projects on the local government's priority list, Wang
aid, are the second phase of the Badaling Expressway;
the building of Ping'an Street, a new thoroughfare parallel to the
well-known Chang'an Street; and sewage treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's construction companies are focusing on the expansion
of the terminal building at the international airport, the
international finance building, the Xidan Culture Square and the
renovation of the Beijing Railway Station.
</P>
<P>
Beijing residents also will see cultural and entertainment
sites mushrooming in the city. They include the Capital Books
Building, the Capital Library, a couple of theaters and some new
urban parks.
</P>
<P>
The city's housing management authorities have decided to
finish residential buildings with a combined floor space of 16
sq. m. in the next two years, Wang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
