<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Denies Presenting Redeployment Plan to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 26 Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said here Thursday that he has not presented a plan to
the United States on the Israeli army's redeployment in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Netanyahu said that no
exact percentage of redeployment has been decided and nothing
will be decided until he consults with the Cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
Early reports said in a message he sent last week to the
U.S. President Bill Clinton, Netanyahu proposed that the scale of
the second withdrawal would probably be "about midway" between
the original Israeli proposal of 9 percent and the 13 percent
urged by Washington.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also said that he is not trying to prevent the
U.S. from introducing new ideas to advance the peace process. But
he stressed that the question was whether " correct ideas" would
be raised.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister noted that he did not believe Clinton will
try to impose his security views on Israel, adding that he is
certain the current Israeli government is doing the right thing.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made his remarks just before the U.S. Middle East
Peace Envoy Dennis Ross arrives here later Thursday for talks
with Israeli and Palestinian leaders in a bid to break the
deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
As a good gesture to the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
ahead of Ross's tour, Israeli officials said Thursday that the
government is considering to release 250 Palestinian prisoners in
the framework of redeployment deal.
</P>
<P>
The PNA said that releasing Palestinian prisoners would be a
confidence building measure in advance of the further withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel Radio quoted Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai as saying that he stands by his statement three months
ago that he will not remain in the government if the peace
process does not move forward.
</P>
<P>
However, Mordechai, who is currently visiting the U.S., said
that he believed the Israeli government was on the right track in
advancing the peace process. He noted that if the Palestinians
fulfill their obligations, the process could progress in a short
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
