<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Publishes Selected Works of Late Mathematician </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- China has published the
selected works of the late mathematician Chen Jingrun, who made a
major breakthrough in proving "Goldbach's Conjecture."
</P>
<P>
The book include his thesis on the proof for "Goldbach's
conjecture 1 + 2" and another 24 theses, which represent the major
achievements of Chen, who died of Parkinson's disease in March
of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Chen was born in east China's Fujian Province in 1933, and
graduated from Xiamen University in 1949.
</P>
<P>
A renowned Chinese mathematician, Hua Luogeng, discovered
Chen's gift in mathematics and offered him a job in the Institute
of Mathematics of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, where Chen in
1966 wrote the thesis about "each large even number can be
expressed as the sum of a prime and an integer that is the product
of at most two primes," or the proof for "Goldbach's Conjecture 1
+ 2".
</P>
<P>
He published a much simplified version of the proof in 1973,
which was recognized as Chen Jingrun's Theorem by mathematicians
all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Springer-Verlag, the world famous science publishing house, has
decided to publish an English edition of Chen's selected works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Ocean Vessels Come to and Go out of Hong Kong in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The number and capacity of
ocean vessels came to Hong Kong increased by four percent and
eight percent respectively in the fourth quarter of 1997 over the
same period of the previous year, official figures showed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, those of outgoing vessels increased by three percent
and eight percent respectively, the Census and Statistics
Department (CSD) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The CSD said that 11,182 ocean vessels with a total capacity of
51.1 million net registered tons entered Hong Kong in the fourth
quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Over the same period, there were 11,177 outgoing ocean vessels
with a total capacity of 51.0 million net registered tons, the CSD
said. Net registered ton (NRT) is a unit measure in volume terms
of the space of a vessel available for carrying passengers or
goods. One NRT is equivalent to 100 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
For the whole year of 1997, the number and capacity of incoming
ocean vessels were 43,294 and 199.0 million NRT, increasing by
five percent and nine percent respectively over those in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number and capacity of outgoing ocean vessels
also increased by five and nine percent respectively to 43,297 and
198.3 million NPT, according to the CSD.
</P>
<P>
In the fourth quarter of 1997, the total tonnage of seaborne
inward cargo, comprising seaborne imports and seaborne inward
transshipment, was estimated to be 24.2 million tones,
representing an increase of four percent over the same quarter in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The respective increases in the total tonnage of suborn imports
and seaborne inward transshipment were five percent and two
percent.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the total tonnage of seaborne outward
cargo, comprising seaborne exports (domestic exports and
re-exports) and seaborne outward transshipment, was estimated to
be 10.6 million tones, representing an increase of one percent
over the same quarter in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Within this total, there was an increase of three percent in
the tonnage of seaborne exports but a decrease of one percent in
that of seaborne outward transshipment.
</P>
<P>
For the whole year of 1997, the total tonnage of seaborne
imports was 75.8 million tones, seaborne inward transshipment 16.1
million tones, seaborne exports 23.8 million tones, and seaborne
outward transshipment 17.6 million tones.
</P>
<P>
Comparing 1997 with 1996, increases were recorded in all these
four types of shipment, with seaborne imports increasing by six
percent, seaborne inward transshipment by seven percent, seaborne
exports by five percent and seaborne outward transshipment by six
percent respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Storm Affects Macao's Export Less Than Expected: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, March 26 (Xinhua) -- A senior Macao economic official
said the financial storms may affect Macao's exports less than
expected, the Macao Daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Maria Cesar, directress of the Economic Department of Macao,
said that local manufacturers have received far more orders than
expected, demonstrating that the currency devaluation in southeast
Asian nations has not severely hit Macao, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
She said the slight drop of imports and exports in January in
Macao was only caused by seasonal factors because most factories
were on vacation for the Chinese Lunar New holidays.
</P>
<P>
She said that the competitiveness coming along with the
devaluation in those nations was weakened by a budget crisis,
which followed the outbreak of the financial storms, and a tight
money policy of financial institutions in those region.
</P>
<P>
Many factories did not have sufficient capital to buy raw
materials, whose price was rising, or even maintain normal
operation, she said.
</P>
<P>
The directress did not elaborate how well orders have been
placed in Macao manufacturers. Local analysts predicted earlier
that Macao's exports may suffer a severe blow this year due to the
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Macao's foreign trade volume reached a record high in 1997,
with an unprecedented trade surplus of 526 million patacas (65.75
million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
