<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tension Mounts Over Clinton's Safety in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Liu Yegang)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Tension is rising between
South African and American security personnel over U.S. President
Bill Clinton's first state visit to the country.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and his 1000-strong entourage arrived in Cape Town on
Thursday morning to start a four-day visit on the fourth leg of
his six-nation African tour.
</P>
<P>
According to local media reports, there is simmering
resentment in the way that the Americans have swooped down on
Cape Town and imposed their authority on their South African
counterparts even to the point of screening those who will roll
out the red carpet.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, while the parliamentary complex was abuzz with
last minute preparations for the address by Clinton later on
Thursday afternoon, problems between the two sides started
emerging.
</P>
<P>
Local officials revealed that they were upset with the manner
in which members of the American secret services had taken over
all the security responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
"Who is in charge?" a source noted, adding that "the current
situation is that the South African security personnel are told
by Americans what to do."
</P>
<P>
Security is so stringent for Clinton's visit that even trees
along the route have been trimmed and manholes on roads,
especially those leading toward a five star hotel where the
president will be staying, have been sealed.
</P>
<P>
As the city of Cape Town braced itself for the three-day
American invasion, Mayor Theresa Solomon stood by her warning to
the city council that she would not be pushed around by
overzealous U.S. security personnel when meeting Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The mayor is not the only public figure taking a stand against
Clinton's security staff.
</P>
<P>
The Speaker of South African parliament, Frene Ginwala, has
apparently ordered that security in parliament for Clinton was to
be handled by South African instead of U.S. personnel.
</P>
<P>
Apparently because of the high-handed behavior of U.S.
security personnel during Vice-President Al Gore's visit last
year, Ginwala decreed that U.S. secret service men were not going
to run the show in her legislature.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday morning, about 150 members of a group calling
itself Muslims Against Global Oppression demonstrated outside the
Cape Town airport to protest Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
Protest organizer Moaim Achmed told reporters that Clinton was
not welcomed on the soil of Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Evil, as we call him, has no idea of peace. He makes war
against our people. We will wait here until he arrives, and give
him a strong message from Muslims around the world," Achmed said.
</P>
<P>
A heavy police contingent prevented the protesters from
entering the airport premises while many army vehicles lined the
route nearer to the airport.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local media is criticizing U.S. policy on Africa.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to editors of the Citizen and the Star, a
Pretorian reader, F.H Osman, said that the United States "poses
the greatest threat to human rights and dignity the world has
ever known."
</P>
<P>
"We must never forget that without the covert and overt
support of the U.S., the white racist regime would not have been
able to sustain for so long. Apartheid is one of the most
inhumane social system in human history," he said.
</P>
<P>
And yet, the reader said, America -- a purportedly passionate
defender of human rights, was prepared to tolerate apartheid in
its own country for many years.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Wednesday on the eve of Clinton's
visit, the South African Communist Party said that Clinton should
acknowledge the role that the U.S. administration played over
many decades in supporting the apartheid regime.
</P>
<P>
The party questioned whether Clinton's trip and his newly
proffered partnership was less about an African renaissance and
more about U.S. business rivalry with former colonial powers.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the U.S. to use its influence to write off the
debt of the most impoverished African countries.
</P>
<P>
"This must be done immediately, for while President Clinton
speaks of an African renaissance, his own administration has been
using its powers to delay implementation of the debt reduction
program," the party said in its statement.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with a French magazine on Wednesday, South
African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki criticized a shift in the
U.S. Africa policy from aid to trade, which was embodied in a
bill brought by Clinton to the continent in his current visit.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said that Africa needs both aid and trade, adding that
international measures should do more than just open up African
markets to sophisticated goods from the developed world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged to Stop Manipulating IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 26 (Xinhua) -- An on-going economic forum on
Thursday called on the united states to stop manipulating the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Asian academics and researchers attending the forum on the
forthcoming Asia-Europe Summit said the U.S. has been manipulating
the IMF to squeeze Asia's battered economics.
</P>
<P>
The forum was designed to draw the attention of the Asian and
European leaders to grassroots issues in Asia when they meet in
London early next month to address, among other topics, the
currency crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Walden Bello, co-director of Focus on the Global South which
organized the forum, urged Europe and Japan to stop the U.S.
manipulation, saying it was in the interests of Europe and Japan
to use their votes in the IMF to stop the U.S. from using the
multilateral organization to squeeze the Asian public sector.
</P>
<P>
The participants also criticized the IMF for making
prescriptions that were bringing recession in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Charles Santiago, a Malaysia-based economist at the Stanford
Center for Economic and Social Research, said: "While Asian
countries are fighting their economic woes, the IMF rescue
package, demanding further liberalization and privatization, has
allowed multinational corporations to take advantage of these
governments and force them to behave in benefit of their (the
corporations') interests."
</P>
<P>
He said Asian countries should adopt measures to monitor and
regulate international financial flows and control speculation
such as lock-in periods and currency transaction tax.
</P>
<P>
He cited a case in South Korea where the Korean consumer
movement campaign on buying Korean-made goods was recently forced
to stop as the Korean government was criticized by German and
British ambassadors who claimed the campaign was against the free
trade principle.
</P>
<P>
Gigi Francisco, a representative from the Philippines said the
forum viewed the IMF prescriptions of squeezing the Asian domestic
economy and expanding foreign investments as detrimental to Asian
women's well-being.
</P>
<P>
"We urge Asian states to implement strict monitoring and
regulation of industrial restructuring and exploitative work such
as prostitution and trafficking to protect women workers' rights,"
said Francisco. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
