<HEADLINE> Bank of Thailand Announces Huge Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand (BOT)
announced Thursday that it suffered massive losses of about 360
billion baht (9.33 billion U.S. dollars) from its general account
in 1997, a BOT official said.
</P>
<P>
The losses were the result of the central bank's build-up of
U.S. dollar liabilities to defend the baht after international
speculators attacked the Thai currency last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the currency reserves account, which backs up the baht
issue in the market, would post huge profits from foreign exchange
gains.
</P>
<P>
BOT Governor Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi chaired a court of directors
meeting Thursday at which the annual report of the central bank
was approved.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time in history that the central bank reported
losses from its general account for 1997, a year that saw the free
fall of the baht from 25 baht to the dollar to 47 by year-end.
</P>
</TEXT>
