<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Offshore Trade Growth Expands HK's Trading Hub Role: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Continuous growth in offshore
trade is strengthening Hong Kong's position as the premier trading
hub and regional headquarters in the Asia-Pacific region, a
spokesman for the Hong Kong Trade Development Council (TDC) said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the findings of a TDC research report on the rise in
offshore trade and offshore investment, TDC's Chief Economist
Edward Leung said Hong Kong's total trading capability continues
to expand, even though export growth has slowed in the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
"This is made possible because of vigorous expansion in
offshore trade and offshore manufacturing investment," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
According to the findings, the estimated total value of
offshore trade undertaken by Hong Kong companies, including direct
shipments and transhipments, amounted to 1,050 billion HK dollars
(134.62 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997, or equivalent to 85 percent
of Hong Kong re-exports.
</P>
<P>
This is well above the 70 percent recorded in the same survey
conducted in 1994 and the 50 percent recorded in the 1991 and 1988
surveys.
</P>
<P>
The report, the fourth in a series of studies since 1988,
surveyed 6,266 Hong Kong companies in last November and December.
It studies the development of Hong Kong's trade, including trends,
estimates and forecasts of offshore trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
Leung noted that the surge in offshore trade stems mainly from
the increase in offshore manufacturing investment and the shift in
shipment modes of cargoes.
</P>
<P>
"Capitalizing on the comparative advantages of low-cost
production in developing Asian economies and Hong Kong's own
business connections, management expertise and infrastructure,
local companies can expand their manufacturing and trading
business beyond domestic production constraints and geographical
boundaries," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the competence of cross-border operations of local
small and medium-sized enterprises provides Hong Kong with an
unmatched advantage as a trading hub amid the worldwide trends of
globalization in production and sourcing.
</P>
<P>
With the gradual shift from re-exports and transhipments to
direct shipments, Hong Kong, however, remains China's most
important enterpot, Leung said. In terms of value, Hong Kong still
handles 40 percent of the Mainland's total exports in 1997, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"The rapidly expanding offshore trade and offshore investment
also stimulate the demand for certain trade-supporting services,
further expanding Hong Kong's role as a trading hub," Leung said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
