<HEADLINE> S'pore, Indonesia to Launch Trade Financing Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Singapore and Indonesia will
launch a bilateral trade financing scheme to facilitate
Indonesia's imports of manufacturing materials and other essential
goods, Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Goh said that this trade guarantee should be backed by at least
two billion U.S. dollars, which will come from Singapore's pledge
to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) package for Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Singapore pledged five billion U.S. dollars earlier to the IMF
package for Indonesia. And the Prime Minister said he might be
able to provide details of the bilateral trade financing scheme
next week.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore television said that Goh made the announcement in
Bangkok at the end of his two-day visit to Thailand, following his
trip to Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister also said that Singapore bankers would be
consulted to take part in the proposed scheme.
</P>
<P>
He said that the scheme, which came at Indonesia's request,
would also have some flexibility built in, so that other countries
could participate later.
</P>
<P>
Exports like those from Singapore manufacturers would be
covered under the scheme, the television report said.
</P>
<P>
It also said that Goh told the Singapore media that his
original proposal for a multi-lateral trade financing scheme
depended on the support of the Group of Seven (G-7) countries who,
so far, had not shown strong interest.
</P>
<P>
The G-7 nations had reportedly said that they preferred their
own financing scheme. 
</P>
</TEXT>
