<HEADLINE> Most Surveyed Companies Intend to Increase Business in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Recent currency devaluations in
some Asian countries have not driven companies out of Hong Kong,
with 90 percent of the surveyed companies still intend to increase
or maintain their trade-economic activities here, a spokesman for
the Hong Kong Trade Development Council (TDC) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
These companies have been eager to expand their operations in
trade finance, business negotiation, market research, insurance,
marketing, trade documentation and arbitration in Hong Kong, TDC's
Chief Economist Edward Leung added.
</P>
<P>
He also said that a recent survey conducted more than 6,266
companies here shows that over 95 percent of the respondents
intend to maintain their controlling headquarters in Hong Kong
compared with the 92 percent in the 1994 survey.
</P>
<P>
"In the long run, the future of Hong Kong as the (Asia-Pacific)
region's most important trading hub rests largely on whether
companies will continue to use Hong Kong as their operational
base," Leung noted. 
</P>
