<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao SAR Land Fund Increases Steadily: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Land Fund of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (SAR) has increased to eight billion patacas
(about one billion U.S. dollars), a senior Chinese official said
here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Yang Runzhen, chief representative of the Chinese side of the
Sino-Portuguese Land Group, said after a meeting of the land fund
investment committee that the outcome of last year's land fund
investment reached 6.4 percent, higher than the official inflation
rate in 1997.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the land fund reached 7.952 billion patacas
(about 994 million US dollars), and it is expected to reach 10
billion patacas (about 1.25 billion U.S. dollars) before the
handover of power in December 1999, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
"The fund has been growing steadily," Yang told reporters. "It
has not only survived the severe test of the financial crisis in
Asia last year, but also gained growth higher than the inflation
rate."
</P>
<P>
Most of the income for the fund comes from the annual land
sale. The Chinese side of the Sino-Portuguese Land Group is
entrusted to manage the fund on behalf of the Macao SAR
Government.
</P>
<P>
Yang stressed that the Chinese side has always abided by the
principle of stability and security in the management of the fund
as the money belongs to the Macao SAR Government.
</P>
<P>
The main form of investment is in bank deposits, said Edmundo
Hau-Wah Ho, who heads the investment committee of the fund. Ho
added that there are also some low-risk and high-credibility
bonds.
</P>
<P>
"We do not do any transactions of stocks or of foreign
currency, so we can avoid being hit by the negative side of the
crisis," Ho said. "In addition, most of our money is deposited in
Macao banks, which were not hit by the financial crisis."
</P>
<P>
"In particular, we gained profits by taking advantages brought
about following the crisis," Ho added. "The higher bank deposit
interests meant an opportunity." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
