<HEADLINE> Nigeria Warns Against Flying over Disputed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Air Force has warned
airline operators to stop flying over the Bakassi Peninsula as
the face-off between Nigeria and Cameroun over the ownership of
it thickens.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement by the force's station in Calabar
near the Nigeria-Cameroun border issued Wednesday, "all airline
operators are hereby warned to desist flying through Bakassi
airspace."
</P>
<P>
Any aircraft that flies through it "will be brought down", the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
The warning, though it did not specify reasons for or the time
limit of the ban, was copied to two oil companies which fly their
workers by helicopters to their respective offshore oil rigs
close to that area.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian and Cameroun have been clashing since early 1994 on
Bakassi, a territory of about 1,000 square kilometers and
believed to be rich in fishery and oil resources.
</P>
<P>
Tension seems to be amounting since February when there have
been a series of reported attacks on Nigerians resident in the
peninsula by forces from Cameroun.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the Nigerian Defense Headquarters said that
Cameroun, using a helicopter mounted with general purpose machine
gun, attacked troops and civilians in several areas of Bakassi,
seriously injuring at least 43 of Nigerians, including 20 market
women and more than 18 school children.
</P>
<P>
The reported attacks may have led to the warning.
</P>
<P>
The dispute over the ownership of Bakassi was filed to the
International Court of Justice by Cameroun in 1994 and is currently
being heard at the Hague, the Netherlands.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
