<HEADLINE> Inspection of First Iraqi Presidential Site Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 26 (Xinhua) -- A group of U.N. weapons experts,
accompanied by senior displomats, started inspections of one of
Iraq's eight presidential sites Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The group, led by deputy chairman of the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) on scrapping Iraq's weapons of destruction,
Charles Duelfer, an American, set out for the suburb of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed diplomatic sources said they are going to inspect
a presidential compound in Radwaniyah, outside Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
 and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz last month, Iraq
agrees to open its eight presidential sites, previously declared
off-limits to inspections.
</P>
<P>
A special group of senior diplomats appointed by Annan and arms
experts from UNSCOM and the International Atomic Energy Agency,
headed by Sri Lankan Jayanatha Dhanapala, was to carry out the job.
</P>
<P>
Dhanapala, who sent a written notice on the inspection the
night before to the Iraqi government, told reporters even he
himself does not know where they are going.
</P>
<P>
"Only Duelfer knows," said an inspector.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. mapmakers, all the eight Iraqi presidential
compounds cover an area of 31.5 square kilometers, including 10
square kilometers of water surface.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler, who ended his five-day visit
to Baghdad and left here Thursday morning, had said there are
1,058 buildings in the presidential compounds.
</P>
<P>
He said it would take about two weeks to finish the inspections
of the first Iraqi presidential compound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
