<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Firms' Success Stories of Participating in SOE Restructuring (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou-based Huangpu Copper
Tube Plant, a financially troubled state-owned enterprise (SOE),
generated a 6-million-yuan profit just eight months after it was
sold to a private firm.
</P>
<P>
After the change of ownership, workers' monthly pay also
climbed to 1,100 yuan (132.5 U.S. dollars), which represents a
good blue-color salary even in affluent Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The transformation of Huangpu Copper is considered a "miracle"
by many people. But to private entrepreneur Qin Dezhao, who bought
the ailing SOE at a cost of 95 million yuan (1.14 million
U.S. dollars), the secret to success is simple: "You have to
cutely play the `trump card' of the market," he said
metaphorically.
</P>
<P>
Like many SOEs, Huangpu Copper heavily relied on the
instructions of government departments instead of what Qin calls
the "trump card" of market demand.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the supplier of refrigerator and air-conditioner
parts suffered from stockpiles of unmarketable products while
infringing on its management initiative.
</P>
<P>
After Qin bought the insolvent firm and renamed it Jianlai
Copper Industry Co. Ltd. in April of 1996, he retained all staff
members but reduced management by assigning more than 100 managers
and technicians to the production line. A responsibility system
was also put in place.
</P>
<P>
A new product development scheme also was vigorously sought,
resulting in six new clients which included refrigerator and
air-conditioner giants Wanbao, Xinfei and Gree.
</P>
<P>
Jianlai made a profit of six million yuan at the end of 1996
and 5.5 million yuan in the first half of 1997 alone.
</P>
<P>
Jianlai is only one example of private firms taking part in the
ongoing restructuring of SOEs in south China's Guangdong
Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Approves $155m for Uganda's Education Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) has approved
155 million U.S. Dollars to support Universal Primary Education
(UPE) program in Uganda, local media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The fund consisted of a 75 million-dollar grant and 80 million
dollars of credit from the WB through its lending arm, the
International Development Association (IDA).
</P>
<P>
The interest free IDA credit is on standard terms of 40 years
maturity (including 10 years grace period) and a 0.75 percent
service charge, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The money will support the educational budget of the country,
said Jim Adams, the WB country director in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The UPE support operation reflects a new flexible lending
policy recently adopted by the WB, the Monitor daily noted.
</P>
<P>
"This operation represents a new way of doing business for the
WB and has been made possible by the important strides Uganda has
made in the management of its economy, said Adams, adding, "the
government has put together a sound project (UPE) which we are
delighted to support."  
</P>
</TEXT>
