<HEADLINE> Private Firms' Success Stories of Participating in SOE Restructuring (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An economic powerhouse in China, Guangdong Province excels in
private economy development with 123,000 firms in 1997, surpassing
all regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
The private sector, which had been a political taboo for a long
time, is currently cited as part of the national economy by
Communist Party documents. Taking advantage of this, the Guangdong
government is encouraging private firms to compete with their
state-run counterparts for a share of restructuring SOEs through
acquisitions, mergers, shareholding and leases.
</P>
<P>
In an asset-injection arrangement, the private Minlian Industry
Co. bought a 42 percent stake in a container terminal, helping the
fund-hungry seaport raise its annual handling capacity to 40,000
containers from 7,000.
</P>
<P>
Haiyin Industry Company, another private player, beat all of
its rivals in bidding to purchase a state-owned factory workshop
in Guangzhou, the provincial capital. This was the first sale of
an SOE workshop to a private player in the province.
</P>
<P>
In Guangzhou, private firms have already pledged to inject 500
million yuan into SOEs, according to the Guangzhou City Federation
of Industry and Commerce. "All government departments should
treasure and support the initiative of private firms," urged
deputy mayor of the city Liu Jinxiang.
</P>
<P>
This "marriage" of state and private sectors will benefit both
parties eventually, market analysts believe.
</P>
<P>
In the reform, more and more unprofitable medium- and
small-size SOEs will be forced to let the market determine their
fates.
</P>
<P>
Those private-sector companies in a position to offer help are
firms with economic strength and sound management, said Long
Guoyi, an official with the Guangdong Provincial Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
In rescuing SOEs, the private businesses themselves can also
improve their own management and technology quality, he said.
</P>
<P>
In particular, they can learn to overcome shortfalls caused by
family-type management and short-term investment behavior
characteristic of many private firms, Long said.
</P>
<P>
However, the process is still far from perfect.
</P>
<P>
One major concern is the absence of laws governing asset
evaluation, debt liquidation and employee resettlement of a state
enterprise taken over by a private firm.
</P>
<P>
"The role of the private firms in the restructuring of SOEs is
like a newborn baby, full of life but fragile," commented Huang
Shaoxiong, deputy president of the Guangdong Provincial Federation
of Industry and Commerce.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Plans to Introduce Secondary Money Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government plans to
introduce a secondary money market to enhance the existing base by
allowing free floatation of treasury bills among the commercial
banks, insurance companies and other non-banking financial
institutions, leading English newspaper The Financial Express
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This will increase liquidity and flexibility in the local money
market, the newspaper quoted sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government also plans to introduce some new market
instruments phase by phase to strengthen the fund management
system in the call money market which is now based on call and
restricted to domestic users, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
A task force in this connection was formed earlier by the
government following a set of proposals submitted by the market
operators of different commercial banks, they noted.
</P>
<P>
In the planned secondary money market, the market players will
be able to operate the treasury bills smoothly with other money
market instruments.
</P>
<P>
At present, Bangladesh Bank, the central bank, operates
treasury bills through auctions giving the opportunity only to the
commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The treasury bills are now becoming more lucrative to the banks
due to higher yields, and the banks have to sell treasury bills or
to discount them at reduced rates to the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government also plans to rationalize the term
measurement of government's treasury bills by introducing
seven-day bills, 15-day bills and 360-day bills step by step.
Presently, the government only sells 30-day, 90-day and one-year
bills to the commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Proper measures will be taken in the planned market to conduct
the operation of treasury bills auction smoothly by reducing the
mismatch between treasury bills settlement and maturity dates,
according to the sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
