<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another Foreign Bidder Pulls out of Zambia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- One more foreign company has
pulled out of Zambia's copper project due to lower copper price
on the world market, Times of Zambia reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Falconbridge has pulled out of the Konkola project consortium
in which it was a participant together with the Zambia Copper
Investment (ZCI), according to the local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The pullout has forced ZCI to open fresh negotiations with the
Zambian government and Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) so
that the project could be developed as a joint venture with the
mining conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
ZCI Managing Director Anderson Mazoka said the decision by the
Canadian mining firm to pull out was based on lower copper price
forecasts on the world market and a review of its priorities and
commitments in other projects.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, another Canadian company pulled out of
the Chambishi mine citing the same reasons.
</P>
<P>
The Chambishi mine now has been offered to a Chinese company.
</P>
<P>
Currently the sale of Nchanga and Nkana divisions of the ZCCM
has hit a snag with the buyers, Kafue Consortium, demanding a
re-negotiation following the fall in the price of copper which
has reduced the cost of the two mines.
</P>
<P>
Due to copper price falls in the international market and
outdated equipment, lack of investment and mismanagement, annual
copper output of the country, one of the biggest copper-producing
countries in the world, has decreased gradually to about 300,000
tons in recent years.
</P>
<P>
To attract foreign investments, advanced technology and
management to revive the stagnating copper production, the
government has invited foreign tenders for the ZCCM mines and
assets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
