<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Attacks US Africa Policy Shift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki had criticized a shift in the United
States' Africa policy from aid to trade, which was embodied in a
bill brought by U.S. President Bill Clinton to Africa before his
current visit.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with a French magazine, Mbeki attacked
significant elements of the U.S.-Africa Growth and Opportunity
Bill, saying Clinton's "formula, trade not aid, is wrong",
Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
Africa, including South Africa, needed both, he said.
</P>
<P>
The bill is expected to be high on the agenda of talks between
the United States and South African governments during Clinton's
three-day visit which starts in Cape Town Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It has been approved by the U.S. House of Representatives and
must now go to the senate.
</P>
<P>
The trade bill seeks to open African markets, replace aid with
trade, and grant better U.S. market access for African exports.
It also envisages debt relief, the creation of an African
infrastructure fund linked to political and market reforms, and a
high-level U.S.-African forum.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said international measures should do more than just
open up African markets to sophisticated goods from the developed
world.
</P>
<P>
The continent needed investment which would allow its
economies to increase their capacity to produce exportable goods
rather than just raw materials, he said.
</P>
<P>
The strategic objective of sustainable development meant that
aid could not be excluded from any framework, Mbeki said, adding
that an overwhelming majority of African countries still needed
development assistance, South Africa among them.
</P>
<P>
"This economy today cannot generate the resources that are
required to address all these urgent problems of poverty which
face us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Development assistance was very important and South Africa had
spoken out against "the reduction of aid to (Africa) which has
been happening."
</P>
<P>
It was important to open up markets of the developed world to
African products, Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
Within the context of World Trade Organization liberalization,
it was necessary to recognize that the United States and poor
African countries like Burkina Faso were not partners of equal
weight which could "enter into an equal bargaining posture," he
said.
</P>
<P>
An approach was needed which regulated world trading patterns in a
way that helped poor countries, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
