<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Rejects Attacks of Human Rights Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- South African Home Affairs
Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi Wednesday dismissed as "inaccurate"
an International Human Rights Watch report on South Africa's
treatment of illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The report was supposed to be released Thursday, but was made
available to South African media earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the National Assembly's home affairs committee,
Buthelezi said the report did not reflect the department's main
activities and highlighted isolated incidents. It also contained
many inaccuracies.
</P>
<P>
The report by the New York-based watchdog group accused the
South African government of serious human rights abuses against
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
It said the group was extremely concerned about the alarming
rise in xenophobia, or dislike of strangers, in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The organization said unpunished attacks on foreigners had
become disturbingly common, and foreigners were regularly
victimized by the police, the army and guards at detention
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The report said South African police often sought out
undocumented migrants in order to extract bribes, identifying
them through arbitrary means such as complexion.
</P>
<P>
It said the organization had interviewed numerous people who
claimed to have been physically abused by South African arresting
authorities and that at least one refugee, Jean-Pierre Kanyangwa
of Burundi, died after he was allegedly beaten in police
detention.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi said such problems were not new, but the department
was in the process of transformation and they were receiving
attention.
</P>
<P>
He said in many cases, remedial action had already been taken
or was in the process of being taken.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, it was preposterous to suggest the
department had to provide five-star treatment to illegal aliens
while more than 50 percent of South Africans lived below the
poverty line.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi's deputy, Lindiwe Sisulu, said the methodology used
by the group was doubtful, and there had been no attempt to be
objective.
</P>
<P>
The group had made no attempt to interview Buthelezi, herself,
other home affairs officials, members of the parliament
committee, or even top police officials, Sisulu said.
</P>
<P>
She also questioned the timing of the report's release -- the
day U.S. President Bill Clinton arrives in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The group is using Clinton's visit to raise its own profile,
she said.
</P>
<P>
The human rights watchdog's Africa division director, Peter
Takirambudde, said it was "shameful" for South Africans to be
hostile to aliens.
</P>
<P>
"During the apartheid era, many African countries opened their
doors to South African migrants, exiles and refugees and paid a
heavy economic price for their opposition to apartheid," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Now that the tables are turned, it is shameful to see how
hostile South Africans have become to today's migrants and
refugees who are in need."
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that there are millions of illegal immigrants
in South Africa, which itself faces severe problems of
unemployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0099 </DOCNO>
