<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Raise Spending on Jails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- South Africa would spend 80
percent more on building new prisons and upgrading and
maintaining existing ones in the coming year, the Correctional
Services Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The department planned to spend 759 million Rand (153 million
U.S. Dollars) in the 1998/1999 financial year, compared with the
422 million Rand (85 million dollars) spent this year, Business
Day paper quoted Deputy Minister Dennis Mokotedi as telling
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The department also planned to spend 647 million Rand (130
million dollars) on building and upgrading prisons in the
1999/2000 financial year, and 808 million Rand (163 million
dollars) in 2000/2001, in terms of government's medium-term
expenditure framework.
</P>
<P>
The country's 230 prisons have long been overcrowded, with a
capacity of 97,000 but a population of 142,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
