<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Reiterates Sovereignty over Disputed Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 26 (Xinhua) - Iran Thursday reiterated its full
sovereignty over three islands in the Persian Gulf, which were
also claimed by the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Tehran radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi expressed
regret that the Arab League foreign ministers' meeting raised the
Iran-UAE dispute over the islands, saying that the Arab and
Islamic countries should be united to counter the common enemies,
particularly Israel.
</P>
<P>
In the final statement at the end of the two-day meeting in
Cairo Wednesday, the Arab ministers voiced support to the UAE's
claim of sovereignty over the three islands. The ministers also
called on Iran to end its occupation of the islands and to solve
the dispute with the UAE peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi voiced Iran's readiness to solve the
"misunderstanding" with the UAE through peaceful means, noting
that Tehran attaches great importance to its relations with
regional Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
One of the priorities of Iran's foreign policies is to
expand relations and cooperation with Arab and Muslims
countries, he said, so Iran welcomes measures to politically
solve disputes between Tehran and Abu Dhabi.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi stressed that the three islands of Abu Musa, the
Greater and the Less Tunbs belonged to Iran, saying that
exacerbating the "misunderstanding" between Iran and the UAE was
not in the interest of the regional countries.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Islamic countries should be united to
counter the Israeli government which was continuing its
aggressive and expansionist policy in the occupied Arab land.
</P>
<P>
Iran took over the three disputed islands in 1972 after
the British colonist forces withdrew from the region. Both
Tehran and Abu Dhabi claimed full sovereignty over the
islands, though they reached an agreement to co-rule the Abu
Musa island after the British pull-out.
</P>
<P>
During the past years, the UAE called for an arbitrate by
the Hague International Court while Iran rejected involvement of
any third party in the issue, stressing that the
"misunderstanding" between the two countries should be solved
through bilateral talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hu Jintao Meets Lao Guests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice President Hu Jintao
met here today with a Lao delegation led by Oudom Khatthiya, vice
president of the Lao People's Democratic Republic (LPDR) and
chairman of Lao Front for National Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
As friendly neighboring countries, Hu said the people of China
and Laos have a long history of friendly exchanges. Leaders of the
two nations in recent years have kept frequent contacts, through
which they frankly and sincerely exchanged views on issues of
common concern.
</P>
<P>
"The discussions are beneficial to the smooth development of
bilateral ties and regional peace and stability, and further
consolidate and strengthen the China-Laos friendly and cooperative
relationship," He said, adding that such meetings are also in the
fundamental interests of the two peoples and meet common wishes of
the two states.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice president highly evaluated the achievements
made by Laos in the process of reform and opening to the outside
world, and believed that the Laos, under the leadership of Lao
People's Revolutionary Party and the newly elected Lao government,
can surmount any difficulty, reach proposed goals and score new
accomplishments in national construction.
</P>
<P>
Oudom said he completely agreed with Hu's comment on the
bilateral ties. LPDR and the Lao government would like to thank
for the long-term support and help given by the Chinese Communist
Party and the Chinese government," he said.
</P>
<P>
He told Hu that in the visit he witnessed the great achievement
made by China in its reform and opening-up drive, adding that the
progress could encourage the Lao people in their own reform and
opening-up cause.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the Lao government and people cherish the
friendly and cooperative relationship with China and want to
advance the existing Laos-China good-neighborly relationship with
the Chinese side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
