<HEADLINE> Casino Magnate Says Macao Casino Business Satisfying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Macao casino magnate Stanley Ho
said that Macao casinos achieved a "quite satisfying business" in
1997, and that he is confident of the future of Macao casinos.
</P>
<P>
A report in Thursday's Macao Daily News quoted Stanley Ho,
general manager of the Macao Tourism and Amusement Company (STDM)
which runs franchise casino business in Macao, as saying on
Wednesday that casino business was better in 1997 than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Ho refused to reveal detailed figures of his casino business
income last year, saying the income would not be announced until
the Macao Legislative Assembly finished discussing about it.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the Macao Jockey Club made a net profit of 41
million patacas (about 5 million U.S. dollars) in 1997. Ho is also
the chairman of the board of directors of the club.
</P>
<P>
Ho, elected a member of the Standing Committee of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC) earlier this month, said he has full confidence
in the future growth of Macao's casinos and Macao's overall
development.
</P>
<P>
He cited his proposal to build a huge sightseeing tower, which
will be higher than the Effeil in France, in the territory to
boost Macao's tourism, as a proof.
</P>
<P>
The tower is to cost some 800 million patacas (about 100
million dollars). It is now waiting for approval by the Macao
Government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
