<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Safety Systems Underway for Turkey's Straits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has started preparations
for setting up new systems to secure safe passage of ships through
its straits, one of the busiest waterways in the world, the Daily
News newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A meeting on these projects was held in Istanbul, bi-sected by
the straits, on Wednesday under the chairmanship of Guven Erkay,
senior adviser of the prime minister's office.
</P>
<P>
"All of these projects will be handed over to the state and
ready to function on January 1, 2000," Erkay, former commander of
the Turkish Naval Forces, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that six groups composed of governmental officials and
experts have been formed to carry out these projects under the
instruction of Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz.
</P>
<P>
Establishing an electronic system to control the ship passage,
choosing highly qualified management staff as well as increasing
the efficiency of the maintenance and rescue operation will be the
key parts of the works, according to Erkay.
</P>
<P>
The straits - Bosphorus Strait, Marmara Sea and Dardanelles
Strait - link the Black Sea and the Aegean Sea. According to
official statistics, 60,000 commercial ships sailed through the
straits last year, which means 150 ships each day.
</P>
<P>
The planned projects to exploit the abundant Caspian oil has
made the government more concerned about the possibility of
increased pollution in the straits, local observers said.
</P>
<P>
Some oil tanks and vessels shipping chemical, radiant and
other dangerous products also pose a serious threat to the health
of local people and the environment of Istanbul, Turkey's largest
city and the most popular tourist destination, as well.
</P>
<P>
The government will provide the finance and will soon invite
domestic and international tenderers to compete for the lucrative
projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
