<HEADLINE> Zambian Former Finance Minister's Company Pounced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Zambian police pounced on former
finance minister Ronald Penza's company here on Wednesday and got
away with property to recover more than 150 million Kwacha (about
100,000 U.S. dollars) it owes its former group financial
controller.
</P>
<P>
The company owes Moonjelly Joseph the 150 million Kwacha in
arrears of salary, inducement allowances, gratuity and other
terminal benefits, Zambia Daily Mail reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Joseph was awarded the money following a high court judgement
in favour of the former financial controller early this month.
</P>
<P>
Penza was dismissed in a cabinet reshuffle last week.
</P>
<P>
The cause for his dismissal has not been given but president
Frederick Chiluba warned his ministers against being arrogant and
inaccessible to the public.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said no leader should personalize government programs
and misdirect themselves into believing that without them such
programs would fail.
</P>
<P>
It is unnecessary for leaders to publicise their possessions
and levels of their knowledge.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba issued the warning four days after he sacked Penza,
who had been holding the portfolio from 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
