<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish Voters Oppose Nuclear Plant Shutdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Only one fourth of the Swedish
voters support the government's decision to shut down the
Barsebaeck nuclear power plant, according to a recent Gallup
poll.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the nationwide survey, conducted for Swedish
evening paper Expressen, were based on interviews with 1,000
persons in different age groups.
</P>
<P>
The results showed that 28 percent of the voters believe
Barsebaeck should be phased out, 55 percent are opposed to the
idea while 17 percent are undecided on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The findings also revealed an opinion gap between men and
women. Barely half of the women protest the planned closure
compared with 66 percent of the men unanimously against the
government's decision.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish government decided on February 5 to close the
Barsebaeck nuclear power plant on July 1 this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Share Market Drifts Slightly Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
retreated for the second consecutive day Thursday, although only
marginally, following its bullish start to the week.
</P>
<P>
The energy sector scored good gains, as did resources giant
BHP, which reached its best closing price since October 8 last
year, aided by options-related trading.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the local bourse lacked direction after a negative
session on Wall Street overnight.
</P>
<P>
"New York was down but nothing seemed to be pushing our market
today -- all in all it was very dull," a Melbourne-based broker
said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index slipped 0.5 points for a close of
2781.1.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index climbed 5.8 points to end at 1189.4
while the industrials sector shed 7.3 points to 4775.0.
</P>
<P>
The energy index was driven 20 points higher to 1659.6 on
continued momentum surrounding better oil prices.
</P>
<P>
BHP ended 8.2 cents better at 16.00 Australian dollars, its
highest close since October 8 last year, when it finished at 16.07
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto was unchanged at 19.60 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The spot price on bullion was trading 65 U.S. cents higher in
Sydney at 298.90 U.S. dollars an ounce at 16:41, local time.
</P>
<P>
Telstra installment receipts ended three cents lower at 3.84
Australian dollars on heavy trade, placing the telecommunications
giant at the top of the turnover table.
</P>
<P>
More than 17.89 million receipts changed hands worth 46.23
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The banking index managed to add 12.8 points to 5746.0.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank rose 11.8 cents to 21.98 Australian
dollars, ANZ gained 10 cents to 10.40 Australian dollars,
Commonwealth Bank of Australia ended 8.1 weaker at 18.32
Australian dollars and Westpac bank firmed two cents to 10.37
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Colonial bank pulled back 11 cents to finish at 4.99 Australian
dollars and Macquarie Bank forfeited nine cents to close at 14.41
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
At 17:03, local time, national turnover was 301.37 million
stocks traded worth 655.12 million U.S. dollars, with falls at 622
outnumbering rises at 462. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Between Australia, NZ to Top 6 Bln U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Trade between Australia and New
Zealand is expected to top 10 billion Australian dollars (6.7
billion U.S. dollars) this year, Australian Trade Minister Tim
Fischer said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The figure is in contrast with the trade volume of 3.8 billion
U.S. dollars between Australia and Indonesia in 1997, according to
 figures released by Australia's official trade promotion agency
Austrade.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, who is also deputy prime minister, told the Australian
 parliament that trade between Australia and New Zealand have been
 growing by an average 11.6 percent a year since 1983, well above
the 8.3 percent growth in Australia's overall trade over the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
He said the Closer Economic Relations Treaty (CER) signed 15
years ago between the two countries had led to a significant
increase in their bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
He said the Australian government reinvigorated the CER over
the past two years following problems caused by the Paul Keating
government's decision to scrap a joint aviation agreement only
days before it was due to come into force.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said the Australian government also re-established the
joint aviation market agreement, and signed a new mutual
recognition agreement on professional standards, which is due to
come into force in May.
</P>
<P>
He said the CER also helped Australia end restrictions on New
Zealand ships involving in domestic coastal trade in Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0114 </DOCNO>
