<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- News that Japan was going to
pump much more money than expected into its faltering economy
boosted the Japanese yen on Thursday, which took the Australian
dollar along with it for the ride.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed on its highs of the local session at
67.17 U.S. cents, up from 66.87 late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After spending most of the local session in a tight range
sub-67 U.S. cents, the unit jumped up in line with the yen when
Japanese wire services reported that Japan's economic stimulus
package would amount to 16 trillion yen, rather than the 10
trillion previously expected.
</P>
<P>
Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party later confirmed the
package would exceed the 16 trillion yen mark.
</P>
<P>
The official release of the package is due later Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
Rothschild Australia Treasury Manager Paul Macarounas said the
market is "still a little cautious of what will be in there and
whether Japan is taking the right measures."
</P>
<P>
It is not expected to contain the big income tax cuts urged by
businesses, politicians and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar also finished the local session at 86.41
Japanese yen from 86.99 yen previously, and at 1.2266 Deutsche
marks from 1.2219 marks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
