<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Areas' Health Sectors to Get World Bank Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Some poor areas in China will
spend 85 million U.S. dollars of World Bank loans on improving
local health care levels, according to the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
The six-year loan project, covering 97 underdeveloped counties
in 10 central and western provinces, will benefit 32 million
people who need better health-care facilities and services, said
Liu Yunguo, an official with the ministry's Foreign Loan Office.
</P>
<P>
"The money will be partially spent on construction or
renovation of township clinics, as well as programs to improve
women's and children's health care, immunization work, control of
tuberculosis and iodine deficiency disease, and cataract
treatments," Liu told Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has agreed to allocate 45.5 million
U.S. dollars in supporting funds when the project is kicked off
in June, he added.
</P>
<P>
This will be the eighth cooperative project between the Chinese
government and the World Bank to provide loans to improve the
country's health sector.
</P>
<P>
The loan project plans to support the establishment of a
cooperative medical insurance system in some rural areas. The
system, raising funds both from rural residents and governments,
will pay most medical expenses for individuals.
</P>
<P>
Part of the loans will also be used to pay fees for women and
children to receive health care and immunizations, as well as 60
percent of the medical expenses of some poor residents, who
account for 5 percent of 32 million people.
</P>
<P>
"Although health budgets were increased in recent years, poor
areas are still under the nation's average levels in terms of
health-care facilities, services and residents' health condition,"
Liu said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the World Bank loan project not only provided
monetary supports, but also introduced advanced technology and
good management models to China's health sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
