<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Reform to Spur China's Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Speeding up the reform of China's
financial sector will enable its stock market to become more
standardized and healthier, said Richard Grasso, chairman and
chief executive officer of the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE).
</P>
<P>
Grasso told Xinhua in an interview here today that the
deepening of China's financial reform will increase investors'
confidence in China's stock markets.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji has reiterated that China will make
thorough reforms in the country's financial sector in three years
by stepping up its central bank's supervision and regulation
functions and by letting commercial banks operate independently.
</P>
<P>
Grasso spoke highly of the rapid development and encouraging
trends in the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges. He said the
trend indicated that China's stock market is becoming more mature
and will play a more important and positive role in consolidating
China's economic development and effective use of funds.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE will further its cooperation with China's two stock
markets by increasing personnel and exchanging technology, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Grasso said that it is too early to comment on the performance
of 17 Chinese businesses and Chinese-funded companies registered
in Hong Kong and Singapore which had stocks listed on the NYSE
because they have been listed for too short a period. However, he
said foreign investors are very interested in China and have
expressed confidence in listed Chinese businesses.
</P>
<P>
He said that several other Chinese companies will be listed on
the NYSE in the near future, and that more Chinese businesses are
welcome.
</P>
<P>
The sound political ties between the United States and China
will help promote the bilateral exchanges and cooperation in
financial sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
Grasso also said that he planned to tell Chinese President Jiang
Zemin during their meeting today that since Jiang toured the NYSE
last year the index has continued to rise. "I will thank him from
the bottom of my heart, and I will thank him for our investors,"
Grasso said.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE is the largest equities marketplace in the world. As
of this March, 3,056 companies had stock listed on the NYSE,
including 345 foreign companies. These companies had 206 billion
shares worth more than 12 trillion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
