<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Tries Herbal AIDS Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has so far conducted
more than 200 AIDS trials in conjunction with the Zimbabwe
traditional healers association to validate claims by some
traditional healers that they can cure people infected with the
HIV/AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Health and Child Welfare, David
Parirenyatwa told parliament Wednesday the trials have so far
seen 200 patients being enrolled to try and validate the
effectiveness of traditional healers therapies on AIDS, according
to the Zimbabwe News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The trials were initiated in 1993 after several traditional
healers claimed they had a cure for the pandemic that kills more
than 500 people weekly in the country,
</P>
<P>
He said the open labeled comparative study began in 1996 with
200 HIV/AIDS patients being recruited and another program based
on defined criteria enrolling 167 patients in 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said follow-ups on the trials were continuing until May
this year.
</P>
<P>
Funding for the programs came from old mutual company and the
Netherlands Embassy in Zimbabwe to assess the effect of
phyto-therapy (traditional herbs) on clinical immunology and
virolgic markets of disease progression.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
