<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Communications Business Volume Stable in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The latest report from the State
Statistical Bureau (SSB) shows that the business volume of China's
communications sectors remained steady in January, with a slight
drop registered in freight traffic and a solid increase in
passenger traffic.
</P>
<P>
China's freight traffic volume was 209 million tons in January,
down 5.2 percent over the same period in 1997. Included are
railway freight traffic of 124 million tons, highway freight of 36
million tons and waterborne freight of 48 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, passenger traffic increased to 445 million persons,
up 7.5 percent on an annual basis. Railway passenger traffic was
77 million, up 6.1 percent; highways, 354 million, up 8.2 percent;
and civil aviation, 4.42 million, up 8.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The cargo volume at principal seaports was 71 million tons,
down 7.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The posts and telecommunications business volume was 16.2
billion yuan, representing an increase of 33.2 percent over the
year-ago period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
