<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Advertising Honored in Asia-Pacific Region Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- China's two institutional
advertising entries won bronze medals in the first Asia-Pacific
Advertising Festival recently held in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that China's institutional advertising
won awards in international competitions.
</P>
<P>
The two ads emerged from China's large-scale institutional
advertising campaigns launched during the last two years, said Jia
Yubin, deputy secretary-general of the China Advertising
Association, in an exclusive interview here today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,077 advertisements and commercials selected from
the countries and regions in the Asia-Pacific area were submitted
in the advertising festival, which was sponsored by major Asian
countries such as China and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Professor Lu Shengzhang, China's first judge of international
advertising competition, said that the result exactly reflects the
current creative level of China's advertisers.
</P>
<P>
Insiders said that the two precious bronze medals should
inspire and encourage China's advertising sector, which was
discouraged after failures in the Cannes Advertising Festival in
1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Heping, director of the Advertising Department of the
State Administration for Industry and Commerce, holds an
optimistic attitude toward the future of China's advertising
sector.
</P>
<P>
"The world is gradually understanding China, as we are
gradually understanding the world," Zheng said. "That foreigners
buy our products also means that they have come to accept our
culture. I believe that, more and more, China's ads will be
honored in international competition." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
