<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Eyes at Far East for Fish Fillets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is setting eyes
on the Far East market for fish fillets exports after the
European Union imposed a ban on the goods since last December.
</P>
<P>
The government has planned a meeting with owners of fish
processing factories in the Mwanza Region on the shore of the
Lake Victoria early next month to look for an alternative market,
Dar es Salaam newspaper The Guardian said.
</P>
<P>
The Minister for Natural Resources and Tourism, Zakia Meghji,
told the paper Wednesday in the city that the meeting will be a
follow-up to a similar one held in Kampala two weeks ago where
ranking officials from Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda met to look for
alternative markets.
</P>
<P>
The minister said there is a potential market in the Far East
where the three Lake Victoria riparian states can export their
fish products.
</P>
<P>
To prevent the spread of cholera, a water-borne disease, the
EU banned fish imports from the three countries since it was
detected in the Lake Victoria region in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO), however, pointed out it
has not documented any outbreak of cholera resulting from
commercially imported food, despite the fact that a minimum of 50
countries in the world have been affected by the epidemic or
endemic cholera each year since 1961.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania used to export 13,000 tons of fish fillets to the
European Union market. Out of the total exports, 7,000 tons were
fresh fish fillets while the remaining is frozen fish.
</P>
<P>
The EU has banned the exports of fresh fish fillets while
exports of frozen fillets are not affected. The embargo will
cause Tanzania a loss of 4.4 billion shillings (about 6.7 million
US Dollars) per year.
</P>
<P>
The fishing industry earns Tanzania 15 million US Dollars a
year, industry sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Cuts Down Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's revenue projection this
year will fall by an estimated 584.4 million U.S. Dollars as a
result of the cut in crude oil production.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Petroleum Resources announced Monday to cut
down its daily production of about two million barrels by 125,000
barrels, in a desperate bid to forestall the downward slide in
the oil price in the world market, along with similar concerted
actions by other oil producers.
</P>
<P>
Revenue estimates from the oil sector for the 1998 fiscal year
were based on production of 2.175 million barrels per day (BPD)
at an official selling price of 17 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear whether the 125,000 BPD cut would be taken
from the 250,000 BPD set aside for domestic consumption or from
the 989,750 BPD set aside for export.
</P>
<P>
Economic watchers, however, have long predicted a review in
the government's revenue projection in this year's budget
following the drastic fall in oil price since the beginning of
the year.
</P>
<P>
The largest oil producing country in Africa, Nigeria has
planned to earn 11.7 billion dollars from oil sources this year,
which contributes the bulk of the 19.3-billion-dollar budgeted
revenue for the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
