<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Downsizing Textile Industry By Destroying More Spindles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangxi Province got
rid of approximately 10,000 old spindles today, as the opening
move in shrinking the textile industry's size.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to destroy 220,000 more and lay off 20,000
workers this year to cut industry losses by a third.
</P>
<P>
The industry will get over 60 million yuan in subsidies from
the central and provincial governments and over 40 million yuan in
soft loans from state banks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Liaoning Province, in the northeast, also started
pruning its textile industry down yesterday by destroying 30,000
spindles. Half of the province's spindles are outmoded and it
plans to destroy 410,000 more this year.
</P>
<P>
Fujian Province, also in the east China, announced today that
it will get rid of 40,000 spindles this year and 113,000 in three
years' time.
</P>
<P>
China wants to have a leaner but more efficient textile
industry to put a stop to its years of losing money. Other
provinces and autonomous regions are going to destroy some of
their old spindles soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
