<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwestern Chinese Province Building New Granary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Shaanxi Province in northwestern
China is trying to turn 60,000 square kilometers of wasteland into
a grain production base in three to five years as part of its
sustainable development program.
</P>
<P>
The land improvement project will use seven billion yuan to
improve some 660,000 hectares of wasteland, and increase annual
grain output by over three billion kilograms, government sources
say.
</P>
<P>
The province produces 10 billion kilograms of grain annually,
and wants to increase its annual grain production to 14 billion kg
by 2000 and 16 billion by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The project mainly covers Yulin and Yan'an prefectures in the
northern part of the province, which have slightly over 28 percent
of the province's total farmland.
</P>
<P>
Agronomists say that the two areas have great potential for use
as a new granary, and that local farmers have been successful in
attempts to try new ways to get higher yields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
