<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Arms Inspector Ends Visit to Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. chief arms inspector
Richard Butler left here Thursday morning, concluding his five-day
visit, during which he and Iraqi officials achieved "concrete and
practical things."
</P>
<P>
Butler, head of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, held three rounds
of talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz on results of
the technical evaluation meetings held in early February on
missile warheads and chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM must certify that Iraq has destroyed all the prohibited
weapons before the U.N. can lift the economic sanctions imposed on
Iraq since 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Butler told a press conference Wednesday evening that he was
satisfied with the spirit of cooperation shown by the Iraqi side
after the signing of U.N.-Iraq deal over arms inspections and
during his visit.
</P>
<P>
He said he and Iraqi officials achieved "concrete and practical
things" during their talks.
</P>
<P>
On February 23, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan signed the
memorandum of understanding with Aziz on peacefully ending the
Iraq-U.N. crisis, under which a special group of diplomats and
weapons experts will be allowed to enter Iraq's presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
That special group, headed by Sri Lankan Janayatha Dhanapala,
is setting out for its first inspection of Iraqi presidential
sites Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Butler said he would pay another visit to Baghdad in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
