<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archaeologists Discover Cave Used By Early Man in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered a 600-sq.m. cave used by early man in Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
This is the second evidence of Early Stone Age life after the
one in Zhoukoudian in the Beijing suburbs, which was found in
1921, according to the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
An archaeologist from the Henan cultural relics bureau says
that early man lived in this place between 100,000 and 300,000
years ago, and that the discovery answered a question about
whether early man had lived in central China.
</P>
<P>
Some 20,000 stone tools, 20,000 fossilized vertebrates, and 17
fire pits were found at the site, which is on a hilly area to the
north of the village of Wangzongdian in Henan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
