<HEADLINE> Ruins of Ancient Battlefield Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The ruins of a battlefield from
the Eastern Jin Dynasty (317-402) was recently discovered in
north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Two historians in Shanxi did a lot field studies and say they
believe that the Battle of Luchuan took place in the modern city
of Lucheng along a 25-km stretch of the ZhuozZhang River.
</P>
<P>
The battle fought in 370 was part of a war between two minority
ethnic groups during the Eastern Jin and, along with the battles
of Guandu, Chibi, and Feishui, is famous for the fact that a
smaller force defeated a much larger enemy, in this case, 60,000
soldiers facing a force five times its size. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cooperative Medical Services Helping Chinese Farmers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese government has been trying to restore the service
in rural areas since the end of the '80s, and Anhui has spent tens
of thousands of yuan on it, and now covers about 30 percent of its
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
It plans to cover 80 percent, according to Hui Liangyu, who
explains that each village clinic has two to three professionals,
who can provide ordinary medical services.
</P>
<P>
Funds for the medical service come from the village and the
farmers. When costs go above 100 yuan, 30 percent of it can be
covered by the fund, Zhou Huozhao, a farmer in the city of Ningguo
in Anhui, says. Once, when he broke a bone that couldn't be
treated by the village clinic, he was transferred to the county
hospital, which charged him more than 1,100 yuan. Fortunately, 30
percent of the cost was paid by the village.
</P>
<P>
And, the number of people needing help at better-equipped
hospitals has declined thanks to improved medical facilities and
personnel at village clinics, Zhang Mingying, a village doctor of
the village of Tongshan in Anhui, says.
</P>
<P>
Setting up a cooperative medical care system is a major task of
the Chinese government to meet WHO criteria for "Health for All"
status.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health announced last July that it will re-open
the cooperative medical insurance system in rural areas by the
year 2010, when at least 80 percent of the country's 900 million
rural residents will benefit from the system.
</P>
<P>
Some provinces like Shandong, Hainan, Anhui, and Hubei have
already made some progress in this. And, for farmers like Zhou
Huozhao who have benefited from the program, participation is no
doubt good, relieving them of the worry of medical expenses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
