<HEADLINE> Clinton Starts State Visit to S.Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- United States President
Bill Clinton arrived at Cape Town international airport Thursday
Morning on the fourth leg of his six-nation African tour.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was accompanied by his wife Hillary, Secretary for
Labour Alexis Herman, Commerce Secretary William Daley,
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater, and his special envoy for
democracy in Africa Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
The Americans were welcomed by South African Foreign Minister
Alfred Nzo and other government officials, the South African
Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Nzo said the visit was significant because it was the first
trip by an American president to South Africa and would
strengthen relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Over 40 local reporters were at the airport for Clinton's
arrival. The 150-member strong White House press corps, which
chartered its own plane, was expected later.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will be officially welcomed by South African President
Nelson Mandela Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. President will address a joint sitting of parliament
later Thursday. On Friday Clinton will hold bilateral talks with
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mandela will accompany Clinton on a visit to Robben island and
will host a state banquet in his honour Friday night.
</P>
<P>
About 150 members of a group calling itself Moslems against
global oppression demonstrated briefly outside the Cape Town
international airport to protest Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
Protest organizer Moaim Achmed told reporters Clinton was not
welcomed on the soil of Africa.
</P>
<P>
The placards included slogans saying: "Clinton go home",
"America go home", and "death to Mr. evil".
</P>
<P>
"Mister evil, as we call him, has no idea of peace. He makes
war against our people. We will wait here until he arrives, and
give him a strong message from Mosles around the world," Achmed
said.
</P>
<P>
A heavy police contingent prevented the protesters from
entering the airport premises. No violence was reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
