<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Reduce Railways Staff Levels by 20% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 26 (Xinhua) -- A National Railways of Zimbabwe
(NRZ) official Wednesday said the recent instruction by the board
to management to reduce staff by 20 percent was a continuation of
a process to restore viability of the loss-making parastatal, the
daily the Herald reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
NRZ public relations manager Herbert Mondlani said the target
had always been to operate with a staff complement of 8,000 which
was the sustainable figure vis-a-vis the traffic levels and
income generated.
</P>
<P>
"While the voluntary early retirement scheme was one of the
measures taken to reduce labour redundancy," he said, adding,
"management has also looked at other less painful ways of
reducing staff costs through encouraging employees to increase
productivity by raising total amount of our traffic levels."
</P>
<P>
He said costs would also be reduced through redeployment and
retraining of staff so that extra labor was re-located internally
to cover critical areas.
</P>
<P>
Recruitment had been frozen, he said, adding that the
rationalization exercise covered all grades including management.
</P>
<P>
The voluntary early retirement scheme was introduced in 1988
to reduce staff levels from 18,000 to an optimum figure of 8,000.
It now stands at 12,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwestern Chinese Province Improving Investment Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region wants to provide a more favorable environment by
halting unreasonable charges and improving efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wenxue, vice-chairman of the region's People's
Government, says that the move is meant to help the autonomous
region open more to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Guangxi used 1.27 billion US dollars worth of
foreign capital, an increase of 23.5 percent over the previous
year. But, to attract more foreign investment, the autonomous
region has a number of regulations allowing joint ventures to cut
payments on 331 items.
</P>
<P>
The government has urged departments to perfect the charges,
and says that foreign-funded enterprises can refuse to pay the
fees if proper and uniform receipts are not provided. And
procedures for approving foreign-funded projects have been
simplified to improve the quality of service and the work
efficiency of government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
