<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Allowed to Dismantle Airbus A320 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Air Transportation
Office (ATO) Thursday allowed Philippine Airlines to dismantle the
Airbus A320 aircraft which overshot the Bacolod airport runway
last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At least 35 Philippine Airlines maintenance personnel are now
working in two shifts to clear the accident site of the wreckage.
The work is expected to be completed the soonest by March 29, the
ATO said.
</P>
<P>
It added that traffic along the avenue where the jet was
resting on its belly had been re-routed to allow cranes and other
heavy equipment to lift the aircraft in portions, beginning with
the tail section, the fuselage and then the wings.
</P>
<P>
Preparatory dismantling from the aircraft's interior was
completed Wednesday night. All recovered avionics, electronics and
other parts will be shipped to Manila.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft had been declared a total wreck by the French
Aviation Authority and Airbus Industrie representatives who came
here to help determine the cause of the accident.
</P>
<P>
Three people on the ground were killed and 150 others injured
when the airbus overshot the runway Sunday night at Bacolod
airport, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that more than a third of the injured have been
discharged from hospitals and some of the injured requiring
special medical attention have been airlifted to Manila. 
</P>
