<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Become One of Most Concentrated Area for Centenarians (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Ceji, a Tibetan woman who lives in
the suburbs of Lhasa, Tibet's capital, is so old that she cannot
say for certain how old she is.
</P>
<P>
She only remembers "being born in the Year of the Ram",
something that helped her relatives reach the conclusion that
she's 103. But, she's still five years younger than the eldest
resident of the Tibet Autonomous Region, on the Qinghai-Tibetan
Plateau, the "roof of the world".
</P>
<P>
Of its 2.4 million people, at least 60 are centenarians, making
the region one of the parts of China with the greatest
concentration of centenarians.
</P>
<P>
And, although Ceji is happy to answer reporters' questions, she
keeps on with the work at hand: licking a spoon clean after making
glutinous rice cakes, and whispers, "Life is excellent."
</P>
<P>
She was born a tenant peasant and now lives with her youngest
daughter and son-in-law. The six-member family has a hectare of
land and a small grocery store, giving them a better life. She
likes to look at the family's ten chickens and six cows, drink
butter tea, play with the kids, and watch TV while seated on the
sofa.
</P>
<P>
She usually goes to bed at eight pm and takes a nap at noon
time, her son-in-law, Qoijor, says, and her three daily meals are
always the same: a bowl of glutinous rice cake with sugar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
