<HEADLINE> Foreign Information Technology Firms Explore Chinese Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- As sales surge in China's
computer market after a winter-long stagnation, more and more
foreign information technology companies are jumping on the
bandwagon for a bigger share in the emerging market.
</P>
<P>
The Motorola Company of the United States this week launched a
Chinese handwriting input system, WisdomPen, to expand its
presence in China's computer market in addition to
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
With Motorola's WisdomPen software, computer users can input
Chinese characters by writing on a special pad. With a
millennium-long handwriting tradition, Chinese will no longer be
required to give up their habit to learn keyboard-based input
standards.
</P>
<P>
A Motorola representative said computers installed with Chinese
handwriting input systems is less than one percent of the
country's total. To promote the use of its advanced WisdomPen
software in China, Motorola will establish chain stores in most
medium- and large-size cities this year, and further reduce
production costs.
</P>
<P>
Another U.S. information technology giant, Hewlett-Packard
(HP), initiated a technical forum in China on March 25 which runs
until April 22.
</P>
<P>
At the HP Megaforum, the company will offer exhibitions and
seminars in six Chinese cities including Beijing, Shanghai,
Guangzhou and Wuhan to enhance the cooperation with Chinese IT
enterprises and local governments in the electronics business
field.
</P>
<P>
HP has signed an agreement with the China Goods Order System,
an ordering network covering 25 Chinese cities, to forge a
strategic partnership which includes technical cooperation in
network-based marketing and networking projects.
</P>
<P>
Other big names such as Lucent Technologies, IBM and Intel have
joined the competition. Bell Laboratories, the
research-and-development arm of Lucent Technologies, has signed a
cooperation agreement with Beijing University on launching a joint
laboratory to develop applications software and data
communications solutions for China's information technology market.
</P>
<P>
Some 3.2 million personal computers were sold in China last
year. China now has nearly nine million personal computers in
use, which is far from meeting the market needs of a nation
with 1.2 billion people, according to industrial analysts
here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
