<HEADLINE> Tibet Becomes One of Most Concentrated Area for Centenarians (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cegi married at the age of 18 and bore seven children, four of
whom are still alive, and she has 36 offspring.
</P>
<P>
Doctors are amazed the health of the Tibetan centenarians and
attribute their longevity to their optimistic attitude about life,
their regular habits, and living conditions.
</P>
<P>
Cering Zhoigar, vice-chairman of the region's People's
Government, said that the rapid economic growth, the improved
living conditions, and a stable social order, have all contributed
to the increase in the number of centenarians.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show an average annual income in Tibetan
townships of 5,130 yuan (620 US dollars), a 140 percent increase
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Food grain, meat, vegetable, and fruit consumption by Tibetans
on average has been increasing a great deal in recent years. The
autonomous region has 2.44 million people, compared to one million
in 1953, and the average life-span has jumped from 36 to 65.
</P>
<P>
"My offspring treat me very well and I never worry about
anything, so I don't think it's any surprise that I live longer,"
the old lady said.  
</P>
