<HEADLINE> Rift Valley Fever Kills 2,000 Sheep in N.Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The deadly Rift Valley has
killed some 2,000 goats and sheep in four villages since February
in north Tanzania's Monduli District.
</P>
<P>
Monduli veterinarian Adam Rwegasira has appealed to the
government to take urgent measures contain the spread of the
disease, Daily News said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the Minister for Agriculture and Co-operatives, Paul
Kimiti, who visited the district assess the alarming situation
Wednesday, the veterinarian said the district needs at least 150
million shillings to buy vaccines for the remaining livestock.
</P>
<P>
The district, close to the Tanzania-Kenya border, has about
300,000 goats and sheep and each dose of vaccine cost 500
shillings, the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
Rwegasira also said they have received 900 vaccines from a
non-governmental organization, Vetaid, but added it was
insufficient considering the magnitude of the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
He named the affected villages as Sinya, Tingatinga, Sinonik
and Matale.
</P>
<P>
The disease, which causes haemorrhagic fever-like illness, has
also killed seven people in the neighboring Ngorongoro District
last month.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the Monduli district officials that the
government will devote all efforts to combat the disease.
</P>
<P>
The government has requested the Food and Agricultural
Organization (FAO) to provide assistance to contain the spread of
RVF, which has caused heavy death toll of people and livestock in
Kenya and Somalia since last November.
</P>
<P>
RVF virus is mainly transmitted by mosquitoes, but human
beings can also be infected by contact with blood or body fluids
from infected animals which may occur during slaughtering the
animals or handling aborted feteses, World Health Organization
(WHO) explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
