<HEADLINE> Ex-Congolese (K) Ambassador Denied Asylum in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official has
revealed that the Zambian government cannot grant political
asylum to former Congo-Kinshasa Ambassador Bongo Lega and others
seeking refuge in the country, state-owned Times of Zambia
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to reports that Bongo has refused to heed to a recall
order from his government fearing persecution and is instead
seeking asylum in Zambia, Home Affairs Minister Peter Machungwa
said in an interview Wednesday there is no basis for granting the
request.
</P>
<P>
Bongo has not formally requested the Zambian government for
asylum but merely intimated his anxieties on going back to
Kinshasa, said Machungwa.
</P>
<P>
The Home Affairs Minister further pointed out that even if he
had applied, Zambia is not in a position to grant his request
because it does not have solid information that former Zaire's
recalled ambassadors or embassy officials face persecution upon
return.
</P>
<P>
Machungwa added that such allegations will be inconsistent
with the current reconstruction process Congo (K) is undergoing
and as a result "there is no basis upon which we can grant the
request for political asylum to the ambassador."
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the Congolese ambassador did not
heed to recalls three times last year for fear of being
persecuted upon his return to Kinshasa amid speculations that he
is a nephew of Mobutu Sese Seko, late former President of the
then Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Bongo was removed from his post after he refused to heed to
the recalls. However, Bongo ignored the decision of the removal.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia also said that Banza Mukaleyi, Vice-President
of Mobutu's popular movement for the revolution, is also in
Zambia seeking political asylum.
</P>
<P>
Mukaleyi is said to have been in Zambia with his two wives and
13 children since last year and has applied for asylum for fear
of reprisals from the current government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
