<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third World Women More Risky in Childbirth: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Women in developing countries
are 40 times more likely to die due to pregnancy and childbirth
complications compared with their counterparts in developed
states, the World Health Organization (WHO) has said.
</P>
<P>
Only 27 maternal deaths occur for every 100,000 live births in
developed countries per year, compared with 480 in developing
countries, the Daily Nation newspaper Thursday quoted WHO as
reporting.
</P>
<P>
For every woman that dies, 30 others develop chronic
debilitating conditions, such as a destroyed birth canal,
resulting in incontinence and infertility, the U.N. health body
said in a bulletin for World Health Day, to be observed on April
7.
</P>
<P>
"Of all the health statistics monitored by the World Health
Organization, maternal mortality is the one with the largest
discrepancy between developed and developing countries," it said.
</P>
<P>
Eastern and western Africa have the highest maternal
mortalities among the developing countries, with as many as 1,000
women dying for every 100,000 live births.
</P>
<P>
Statistics compiled by WHO indicate that the lifetime risk of
a Kenyan woman to die due to pregnancy-related complications is
one in 20, compared with one in 8,700 in Switzerland or one in
9,200 in Spain, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
This is attributed to very limited access to basic medical
care during pregnancy, child delivery and the post-parturition
period, compounded by lack of political will to provide
accessible and affordable midwifery care.
</P>
<P>
"In developed countries...every pregnant woman has access to
special care during pregnancy and childbirth," said WHO.
</P>
<P>
"Such is not the case in many developing countries where each
pregnancy represents a journey into the unknown from which all
too many women never return," it noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Exports Continue to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's balance of
merchandise trade continued its downward trend in February,
recording the first February deficit since 1992, said Statistics
New Zealand in a media release received on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The office blamed the Asian financial crisis for the poor trade
results as exports to Asia slumped 25.2 percent in the month.
</P>
<P>
Figures for the provisional trade balance for February showed a
deficit of 18 million NZ dollars (10 million U.S. dollars),
contrary to financial market expectation of a surplus of 118
million NZ dollars (66 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
New Zealand has run a trade deficit in recent months.
Traditionally, the trade balance is in surplus from December to
June.
</P>
<P>
While exports are falling, imports are rising because of a
weaker NZ dollar.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Indonesia, New Zealand's fastest growing overseas
market, dropped sharply by 20 million NZ dollars (over 11 million
U.S. dollars) in February to only 6 million NZ dollars (3.4
million U.S. dollars). Sales to South Korea also fell in the
month.
</P>
<P>
The hardest hit export sectors are hides and skins, down 28
percent in the past three months, followed by wood, down 10
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
