<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Optical Fingerprinter to Replace Inked Fingerprints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
developed an optical fingerprint-collecting device which is
expected to replace the traditional manual method.
</P>
<P>
With the touch of a finger on a match-box-size glass window,
the apparatus will message the main computer and compare
fingerprints within seconds.
</P>
<P>
The optical device not only collects a picture of a finger, but
it can also record a three-dimensional image to meet the needs of
public security departments.
</P>
<P>
The apparatus, developed by scientists from the Changchun
Institute of Optics and Precision Machines -- China's top optics
research center -- has been approved by the Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
Zhou Wanzhi, associate research fellow at the Changchun
institute attached to the CAS, said part of the performance of the
apparatus is apparently better than that of foreign ones.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that, in comparison with the similar U.S. product,
the Chinese apparatus is much smaller and cheaper, and its images
have a smaller margin for error.
</P>
<P>
Deng Ruiyu, head of the Science and Technology Division of
Jilin Provincial Public Security Department, said police
departments have been using ink to put fingerprints on paper
which are kept with special cards.
</P>
<P>
He said it would take a lot of work to compare collected
fingerprints with the stored fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
As ink cannot be put evenly on the fingers, 70 percent of the
inked fingerprints are not qualified for detectives' work.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said the optical fingerprint-collecting apparatus could be
widely used by police in identifying criminals, by banks for
withdrawals, and by companies to secure computer data and provide
fingerprint locking devices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
