<HEADLINE> Dhaka Attracts 1.5 Bln Dollars in Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Foreign businessmen invested about
1.5 billion U.S. dollars in Bangladesh in the 18 months up to last
December, Board of Investment (BOI) Chairman Farooq Sobhan said.
</P>
<P>
From July 1, 1996 to December 31, 1997, a total of 2,137
projects were registered with the BOI worth an estimated 3.4
billion dollars, Sobhan told a visiting Singaporean mission in
Dhaka Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The service sector attracted the most foreign investors during
the period, he added.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-three percent of the investment proposals came from Hong
Kong, 12 percent from Malaysia, 8 percent from South Korea and 7
percent from Singapore, he said.
</P>
<P>
The BOI chief also briefed the Singaporean mission on the
Bangladeshi government's policies and measures for attracting
foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
The Singaporean mission representing both public and private
sectors was jointly organized by Singapore's Trade Development
Board and Confederation of Industries. It came to this South Asian
country to seek opportunities for investment in infrastructure
projects. 
</P>
