<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cooperative Medical Services Helping Chinese Farmers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in east China's Anhui
Province don't necessarily need to travel a long way to see a
doctor, thanks to a cooperative medical service.
</P>
<P>
One farmer, Fu Liang, had a problem with chronic stomach
trouble, but when he suffered a recent bout he got help right away
when the doctor in his village went to his home and it only cost
him a little over 100 yuan (12 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
It was only a few years ago when a sudden attack like that
would have forced him to travel several miles to see a doctor at
the county hospital and it would have cost him more than 500 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Fu doesn't have to worry about his illness anymore because of
the cooperative medical service, which allows farmers to pay only
part of their medical costs, with the collective they belong to
paying the rest.
</P>
<P>
The service started in rural areas in the 1950s, but wasn't
widely used. After 1979, the service went into a period of decline
because of wide-ranging reforms, according to Quan Yunzhen,
vice-director of the Anhui Health Department, and by 1985, it
covered fewer than ten percent of China's rural people, and only
1.2 percent of Anhui's rural people.
</P>
<P>
The decline in service caused some rural families to become
impoverished when a family member became seriously ill, Quan
explains. China's rural people often face unexpected medical
costs, and in poor areas, the expression "going to hospital",
became a metaphor for hard times.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health says that more than 30 percent of
poverty-stricken people in rural China were burdened with medical
expenses, which could easily cost a farmer a year's income if the
disease was bad enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
