<HEADLINE> China's Largest Cotton Producer Getting Rid of Outmoded Spindles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 26 (Xinhua) -- 10,000 outmoded spindles in Mill
No.2 of the Textile Group of China's Xinjiang Uighur Autonomous
Region were recently destroyed.
</P>
<P>
This was the opening salvo in a campaign to get rid of 180,000
spindles within three years in China's largest cotton production
center and also a nationwide campaign to get rid of 10 million
spindles in the same period of time.
</P>
<P>
One 53-year-old Uygur employee, Abdurahim Kerim, was standing
there affectionately preparing to get an axe to stroke the
40-year-old spindles, with tears welling up in his eyes. But he
said philosophically, "Getting rid of the old spindles not only
benefits the mill and the state but also we workers, because the
machines, like retired workers, have done what they could."
</P>
<P>
The action left more than 800 workers without job. But, they
felt somewhat relieved when they got the news that the central and
local governments had given the mill three million yuan in
subsidies to help them find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
An 18-year-old girl, Sun Ming, didn't seem too worried about
her future and explained, "I guess I'll be given another post in
the mill." The mill's director seemed to confirm that when he said
that some new projects are being planned to re-employ most of
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
