<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Exports Up, Imports Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam had a mixed change in
foreign trade in the first quarter, with exports increasing by
12.2 percent and imports down by 2.6 percent compared with the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show the country is expected to earn an
export revenue of 2.2 billion U.S. dollars in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Exports by foreign invested enterprises are estimated at 420
million dollars, up 33.8 percent over the first quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Rice led all export items with 1.2 million tons shipped abroad,
2.5 times higher than the same period last year. The country plans
to export four million tons of rice this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the export growth rate in the first quarter was low
due to price reductions of several main export items, especially
crude oil.
</P>
<P>
Other exports such as textiles, garments and footwear are
facing fierce competition with other countries in the region which
are severely affected by the current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Import turnover in the first quarter is expected to reach 2.65
billion dollars, down by 2.6 percent from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Imports of cars and car parts, cement, clinker and medicines
have dropped sharply. Imports by foreign-invested enterprises in
Vietnam are estimated at 651 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
