<HEADLINE> Interest Rate Cut Helpful to State Industry Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 26 (Xinhua) -- China's recent interest rate cut
will greatly help state industry reforms by alleviating burdens
and fund shortages, according to a senior banking official.
</P>
<P>
Mao Yingliang, president of the Shanghai branch of the People's
Bank of China, the central bank, said that, since 1995, China has
reduced interest rates on loans four times by an average of 4.05
percentage points, and the interest rate on one-year loans was cut
by more than 30 percent, which will be particularly helpful to
Shanghai's state-owned firms.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China announced Wednesday that interest
rates on deposits and loans will be reduced 0.16 and 0.6
percentage points respectively.
</P>
<P>
The bank announced that a reform of the deposit reserve fund
system will begin and that interest rates on loans and deposits of
financial institutions will be lowered.
</P>
<P>
The bank has lowered the interest rate on deposits of financial
institutions from 7.35 percent to 5.22 percent, and interest rates
on loans to financial institutions went down from 9.19 percent to
7.43 percent.
</P>
<P>
Mao praised the move, saying that it will increase the reserves
of financial institutions and enhance their ability to support
the development of local state-owned companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
