<HEADLINE> Romania Issues Treasury Bills to Stabilize Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Romania issued another 200
billion leus (around 244 million U.S. dollars) in treasury bills
on Thursday to help stabilize the state currency.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Affairs for the Finance Ministry Ionut
Costea said the annual interest rate for the three-month bonds
will drop from 75 percent to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Costea said the reason for the cut in the interest rate for the
short term bill is because the inflation rate is expected to fall
in the months to come.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft budget, Romania will try to rein in the
inflation rate at about 45 percent, far below last year's 151
percent.
</P>
<P>
Costea said the bills will be issued through the country's
savings banks (CEC).
</P>
<P>
Eliza Sirbu, spokesman of the CEC, said all of the 180 CECs
nationwide will extend their business time, given the great
passion people showed for the previous issue in the past two
months.
</P>
<P>
Romania issued 100 billion leus of treasury bills in January
and 200 billion in February.
</P>
<P>
Economists here believe the move intends to draw cash from
working people so as to further achieve a stable currency by
constraining the circulation of money.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, the devaluation of Romania's
state currency has been restrained. The exchange rate of leu to
the U.S. dollar has stabilized at 8,200 leu to one U.S. dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
