<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Take Stern Action Against Spurious Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
take stern actions against marketing and selling spurious drugs
which endanger lives of patients, national English newspaper The
New Nation reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This warning was issued by Minister for Health and Family
Planning Salahuddin Yusuf while speaking at a meeting in Dhaka
recently.
</P>
<P>
There are about 200 pharmaceutical factories in Bangladesh
which produce 95 percent medicine for the country, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
The government would submit a bill to the parliament to control
the activities of the "mushroom growth" diagnostic centers and
clinics as well as the drug business, banning all activities
designed to deceive the poor patients, the minister disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The health minister urged all the drug manufacturers not to
allow production and marketing of spurious drugs, and drew
attention of the drug administration to take action against
selling low grade medicines.
</P>
<P>
He requested the drug producers to get their medicines tested
at the drug testing laboratory before marketing.
</P>
<P>
"We must stop deception of innocent people," in this context,
he said, adding putting up deceptive ads in print media should be
stopped, and the country has introduced three-year jail term and a
fine of 0.3 million taka (about 6,521 U.S. dollars) for the
offenders.
</P>
<P>
Value addition in drugs is 70 percent while this sector is the
second highest contributor of revenue in the form of VAT after
cigarette, therefore some drug factories produce and market
spurious medicines for big profit, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
