<HEADLINE> Four South Korean School Girls Commit Suicide Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Four South Korean middle school
girls committed suicide by jumping off a high-rise building
together Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The four girls jumped from a corridor on the 20th floor of the
high-rise building, where police found their lined up shoes,
shirts and notes which carried their last words before death.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy which shocked the nation was the second such
collective suicide by middle school girls this year. It occurred
at Chongyangri, Seoul, at 6:30 p.m. (local time) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In January, three middle school girls killed themselves
together.
</P>
<P>
A teacher of the four girls said they were good students but
their home lives were unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
A note by one of the four read: "I really hated my father's
drunken frenzy. Problems at my home are always money, money and
money. My parents have just never been interested in my agony."
</P>
<P>
The media attributed increased suicides to mass layoffs and
mounting bankruptcies since the country entered "IMF period" last
December.
</P>
<P>
Since entering the "IMF period", every month has seen South
Koreans, predominantly businessmen, kill themselves because of
financial troubles.
</P>
<P>
South Korea signed an agreement with the International Monetary
Fund last December for a rescue loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars
after suffering a serious financial crisis in the second half of
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
