<HEADLINE> SLankan Doctors to Strike Against Official's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Government Medical
Officers Association (GMOA) was to launch a nationwide 24-hour
token strike excluding the north and east on Thursday, The Island
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
GMOA secretary Prasanna Gunawardena was quoted as saying that
the strike was a protest against the appointment of a junior to
the post of deputy director general of medical services over more
qualified and experienced candidates.
</P>
<P>
The GMOA demands that the interview for the post be held again
with a member of the GMOA also included in the Selection Board.
</P>
<P>
Gunawardena said several candidates had complained that they
were not given a fair chance at the interview.
</P>
<P>
The GMOA said there should be no political interference and
that selection should be based on qualification and experience,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The GMOA had given ample time to the minister of health and
indigenous medicine to correct the alleged irregularities and he
will have to take responsibility for any inconvenience and
suffering done to patients, it said.
</P>
<P>
The minister had recommended that the GMOA take legal action to
resolve the issue which the GMOA views as not feasible.
</P>
<P>
The post is of immense importance as whoever holds it decides
the transfer and appointment of medical officers, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the GMOA is to meet tomorrow to decide on further
actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
