<HEADLINE> Thai PM Orders Retaliation to Refugee Camp Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minster Chuan Leekpai
ordered all-out retaliation to any intrusions on Thai soil by
armed groups from Myanmar as Rangoon has denied any responsibility
for a series of cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
In his strongest response so far to the western border problem,
Chuan said he will order the Thai army to be in the full operation
of retaliating.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Myanmar embassy in Bangkok has denied that the
Myanmar government has any responsibility or involvement with the
cross border attacks and therefore cannot prevent them.
</P>
<P>
Camps for Myanmar refugees in Tak and Mae Hong Son provinces in
northern Thailand had been attacked by armed forces from
neighboring Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry on Tuesday named the intruders as the
Democratic Karen Buddhist Army (DKBA), which is said to be
connected to the Myanmar government.
</P>
<P>
At a defense council meeting, Chuan, who is also defense
Minster, said he planned to merge the existing 19 Thai camps into
11 and move them deeper into Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also approved the Foreign Ministry's
proposal that the United Nations High Commission for Refugees
(UNHCR) would be allowed to get involved, saying it will allow the
U.N. body to realize the existing problem.
</P>
<P>
He said the UNHCR will have a greater opportunity to inspect
the Thai authorities' administration of the camps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
