<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Enacts Laws to Protect Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Nicaraguan National Assembly
(parliament) Wednesday approved by majority vote a law to protect
children's rights.
</P>
<P>
"This code is like a small constitution because it guarantees
the rights of children, who will benefit from a specialized health
system and education undertaken by public policies," said Jurist
Sergio Cuaresma, one of the authors of the document.
</P>
<P>
The law, approved by 65 majority votes within the legislature,
consists of 234 articles.
</P>
<P>
"At least the first step has been taken, now the actual
enforcement will be the most difficult point," said Sergio
Cuaresma.
</P>
<P>
Dora Zeladon, president of the Children and Teenagers
Parliamentary Commission, said a committee will be set up to take
charge of enforcing the law.
</P>
<P>
The law establishes that all children, girls and boys, have an
intrinsic right to life.
</P>
<P>
It also regulates that contracts involving hard manual labor
are prohibited for children under 14.
</P>
<P>
Zeladon said the first step to be accomplished is to provide
educations for more than 200,000 children who are not attending
school at present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain Pleased to Be Among Euro Favoreds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Spain, once viewed as one of the
countries having trouble in meeting the single currency criteria,
announced Wednesday it was pleased to be among the 11 countries
recommended by the European Union (EU) to join the monetary union.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive body, named
Austria, Belgium, Finland, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy,
Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal and Spain as having met the
criteria to join the single currency, called the euro, on January
1.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar said the decision was great for
Spain and for the European continent as a whole. What used to be
unthinkable comes true, he said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Abel Matutes Y Juan said what Spain had done
to qualify for the single currency now seemed worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
Aznar's government, since coming power in 1996, has managed to
sustain rapid economic growth and bring down its inflation through
austerity policies and fiscal reforms.
</P>
<P>
Spain's gross domestic product (GDP) growth in 1997 was 3.3
percent, compared to a government prediction of three percent and
an average of 2.8 percent among other developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Spain's inflation was 1.9 percent, 0.8 percentage
points lower than the required 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
To qualify for the single currency, a country must lower its
budget deficit to three percent of the gross domestic product
(GDP), and its public debt to 60 percent of GDP. Its inflation has
to be no more than 1.5 percentage points higher than the average
figure of the three best performing countries.
</P>
<P>
The final decision on who's in and who's out will be made at a
summit of the 15-member EU on May 2 in Brussels. Britain, Denmark
and Sweden don't want go in with the first wave. The only member
left out of the proposed list was Greece which slipped past the
deficit figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
