<HEADLINE> Foreign Investments in Latin America Rise Sharply in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Direct foreign investments in
Latin America last year went up 15 percent over the previous year
to 42 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by the World Bank Tuesday said Brazil and
Mexico were the major foreign capital recipients last year to
reach a combined total of 28.24 billion dollars, accounting for 67
percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Brazil absorbed the largest amount of the foreign investments
with 16.8 billion dollars, followed by Mexico with 11.34 billion
dollars, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, direct foreign capital inflow to the
region will definitely slow down in 1998 because of the Asian
financial crisis and the oil price plunge in international
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
