<HEADLINE> DPRK in Urgent Need of More Food AID: WFP Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The visiting United Nations
World Food Program (WFP) executive director, Catherine Bertini,
said here Wednesday the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK) was in urgent need of more food aid.
</P>
<P>
Bertini said the DPRK's grain reserves dropped sharply due to
the devastating floods and drought in the past two consecutive
years. About 7.5 million people, especially children, were
expected to get not enough to eat this year.
</P>
<P>
Last year, about 4.7 million people of the DPRK enjoyed food
assistance from the WFP, half of them being children below
six. More food assistance was sought in the international
community by the program at the beginning this year.
</P>
<P>
Bertini said, there are still other countries as well as the
DPRK in urgent need of food aid. They include Afghanistan, Sudan,
Somali, Ethiopia and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During her stay, Bertini met Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari, and exchanged views on further cooperation of the two
sides. Finland provided 70 million Finland markka (about 11
million U.S. dollars) to the WFP for aid programs last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the WFP, one seventh of the population around the
world was going hungry. About 45 million people in 84 countries
enjoyed aid from the program last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
