<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Says No to Foreign Mediators on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Since the Kosovo issue is an
internal affair of the Republic of Serbia, the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia refuses to receive any foreign special envoys for
mediation of the issue, Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivorad
Jovanovic said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released by the Tanjug news agency, Jovanovic
siad that, however, it is acceptable to have the former Spanish
Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez visit Yugoslavia as a
representative from the European Union (EU) and the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
Jovanovic said that for Yugoslavia, Gonzalez was first of all a
distinguished statesman in Spain and Europe at large.
</P>
<P>
Such a figure, now as a representative of the EU and the OSCE,
would surely be able to enhance the relationship between
Yugoslavia and the two organizations, the Yugoslav foreign
minister believed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the Kosovo issue earlier on Tuesday, Milorad Dodik,
prime minister of the Republic of Srpska, warned that constant
exertion of pressure by some countries on Yugoslavia would produce
a serious negative impact on his republic.
</P>
<P>
Dodik was quoted by the Yugoslav daily, Politika, as saying
that foreign pressure on Yugoslavia had greatly boosted the morale
of the ultra-nationalists in the Republic of Srpska.
</P>
<P>
He said if the situation persisted, the work of his government
would be plunged into confusion.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, he cautioned, regional destabilization could
possibly result, and this might pose a threat to the
implementation of the Dayton peace accords. 
</P>
</TEXT>
