<HEADLINE> Peru's Mining Exports Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Peru's mining exports increased by
82 percent during the period of 1990-1997, a Peruvian official
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from these exports rose from 480 million U.S. dollars
in 1990 to 2.7 billion dollars in 1997, Minister of Energy and
Mines Daniel Hokama said.
</P>
<P>
The rise of gold and copper production was predicted to help
mining exports surpass 2.8 billion dollars this year, an increase
of 3.7 percent, compared with 1997.
</P>
<P>
Hokama said iron production was predicted to reach three
million tons in 1998 and gold production 80 tons. Silver was
predicted at 94 tons and tin, 30,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian government worked out a plan to increase the
annual mining production by 15 percent to double the export value
in the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
