<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Popov Beats Klim, Winning 100m Freestyle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 25 (Xinhua) -- World and Olympic champion Alexander
Popov of Russia claimed his second consecutive World Cup
short-course victory in Imperia, Italy on Wednesday, beating
Australian Michael Kilm to win the 100m freestyle event.
</P>
<P>
Popov, who won the distance in Gelsenkirchen, Germany, last
weekend, swept home in 48.69 seconds ahead of Australia's Chris
Fydler, who was clocked at 48.93.
</P>
<P>
Klim, who took seven medals at last January's world
championships in Perth where he finished second to training
partner Popov in the 100m freestyle, had to settle for third in
49.15.
</P>
<P>
Klim suffered another reverse in the 50m butterfly in which he
was beaten into second place for the second time in five days by
Canada's Garret Pulle.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's Patrik Isaksson and Britain's James Hickman continued
their good form, winning the 200m breaststroke and the 200m
butterfly respectively.
</P>
<P>
Isaksson swam 2:09.34 to beat Russia's Olympic bronze medallist
Andrei Korneyev and world short-course champion Alexander Goukov
of Belarus. Korneyev was timed at 2:10.04 and Goukov at 2:10.73
respectively.
</P>
<P>
World short-course champion Hickman dominated the butterfly,
finishing in 1:54.21 -- more than a second-and-a-half ahead of
second placed Ukrainian Denys Sylantyev, winner of the world
long-course title in Perth.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica's Claudia Poll scored a double victory in the 200
and 800m women's freestyle, as did Germany's Sandra Voelker in the
50m backstroke and 50m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Poll won the 200m in 1:58.45, more than four seconds outside
her own world record, and then finished comfortably ahead of
Kirsten Vlieghuis of the Netherlands in the 800m.
</P>
<P>
Voelker broke 25 seconds to win the freestyle sprint after
finishing more than half a second ahead of Hanna Kapachenia of
Belarus in the backstroke.
</P>
<P>
Denmark's Mette Jacobsen won the 100m butterfly in 59.63. She
is due to attack her own European record in the 200m butterfly,
set last week in Malmo, on Thursday's second day of races.
</P>
<P>
Imperia is the penultimate venue of the nine-round World Cup
series in 25-meter pools. The last round is in Paris next
weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
