<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Unemployment Surges to 8.7 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The number of unemployed people
in Indonesia had doubled from 4.4 million last year to 8.7 million
at the end of February, an official here said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the number of people working less than 35
hours per week had doubled from 9.1 million last year to 18.4
million, Sri Harto, Spokesman for the Ministry of Manpower said
here Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
This pool of labor, including those who work for only several
hours per week, are often referred to as the partially unemployed,
or disguised unemployment, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Together, the number of the unemployed and the partially
unemployed of 27.1 million had doubled last year's total of 13.5
million, Sri said.
</P>
<P>
Sri said that with economic growth forecast to come to a
standstill this year, an estimated 2.7 million new entrants to the
labor market could not be absorbed into the country's workforce.
</P>
<P>
He also said the number of workers dismissed by companies
troubled by the monetary crisis had reached over 1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
Sri predicted that the unemployment rate will rise again this
month, as troubled companies are still dismissing workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
