<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Government, Rebels Sign Secret Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian
government and one of the country's major rebel groups signed a
secret agreement in February to hold preliminary peace talks, a
senior government official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Spain-brokered agreement was signed in Madrid on February
9, when Colombian President Ernesto Samper stopped there following
a visit to the Vatican, said Jose Noe Munoz Rios, a presidential
counsel for peace.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the rebel National Army of Liberation
(ELN) is expected to hold talks with the government on May 31 and
again on June 21.
</P>
<P>
Munoz Rios said the talks would pave the way toward an eventual
national convention aimed at ending the country's 35-year-old
civil war.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that the Revolutionary Armed Forces
of Colombia (FARC) would follow the example of the ELN and also
join the talks. The FARC and the ELN are the two guerrilla groups
attempting to overthrow the government of President Ernesto Samper.
</P>
<P>
The ELN, a Cuban-inspired organization headed by former Spanish
priest Manuel Perez, is Colombia's second largest guerilla
army. FARC is Colombia's largest and oldest guerilla group.
</P>
<P>
The ELN claims Samper used Cali cartel drug money to bankroll
his 1994 election campaign
</P>
<P>
Explaining why the agreement was signed in Madrid, Munoz Rios
said the Spanish government has been working as a friend and
mediator for negotiations between the government and the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0225 </DOCNO>
