<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Chinese Farmers Looking For Better Forms Of Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Yang Hulin, a farmer in
northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, can now grow
cabbage even during the winter months, and has enough power for
his lights and for cooking thanks to a solar-heated greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
The plastic-covered greenhouse uses the sunlight to ferment
manure and the methane it produces for lighting and cooking and
the residue is used for fertilizer for his vegetables.
</P>
<P>
This is actually an environmentally-friendly form of energy
produced by the methane-generating pits, the livestock and poultry
sheds, the lavatories, and the solar greenhouses, according to Li
Guangren, the director of the region's Energy Station for Rural
Areas, who is in charge of a project to develop these sources of
energy.
</P>
<P>
It was started by the Ministry of Agriculture to increase
farmers' income and to use the methane-generating pits to help
them get through the winter months.
</P>
<P>
One county was chosen as a pilot area last August, and five
methane-generating pits have been built, each producing 0.9 to 1.3
cubic meters of methane daily, enough for a six-member family to
cook three meals a day. One pit can also save more than two tons
of coal and 500 kwh of power from other sources annually.
</P>
<P>
The success of the new method has made it possible for pigs to
gain weight faster in winter, farmers to have new fuel, to use
less chemical fertilizer in greenhouses, and to improve the
environment and sanitation in rural areas, according to Cui
Yongqing, director of the region's Agriculture Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
