<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Lowers Oil Production By 70,000 BPD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has decided to lower
its oil output by 70,000 barrels per day (BPD) to 1.39 million
BPD, a senior official announced.
</P>
<P>
The decision would begin to take effect on April 1, Mines and
Energy Minister Kuntoro Mangkusubroto said here Wednesday at a
discussion on oil prices and output.
</P>
<P>
The reduction was part of an agreement reached by the members
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to
stabilize oil prices which had dropped to a record low of 10 U.S.
dollars per barrel, Antara News Agency Thursday quoted the
minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
OPEC members had earlier agreed to lower their oil output to
25.033 million BPD from 27.5 million BPD as agreed upon at the
Jakarta meeting last November.
</P>
<P>
Some other OPEC members and non-OPEC member had also announced
their plan to lower oil production. Oil price soared to 15 U.S.
dollars per barrel after the announcement.
</P>
<P>
Kuntoro asked all OPEC members and independent oil producers to
voluntarily cut their output to prop up the crude oil price.
</P>
<P>
OPEC oil supplies now account for about 40 percent of the
world's total output of 75 million BPD.
</P>
<P>
OPEC members are Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Libya,
Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the united Arab Emirates and
Venezuela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
