<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taxi-drivers in Nanning Win Awards For Fine Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Visitors to Nanning, capital of
south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, often see taxis
that have the Chinese character "jiang" inlaid on the top light.
</P>
<P>
There are 429 taxi cabs with this sign in Nanning, proof of
their excellent service. These cabs are also the most profitable,
for the token of "jiang" tells passengers of the drivers'
reliability, which is good for business.
</P>
<P>
The award is only one measure taken by the local authorities in
a campaign to improve the quality of taxi service.
</P>
<P>
Overcharges and inaccurate meters draw the concern of taxi
passengers everywhere. Three years ago when Zhang Shan, an Olympic
gold medal winner, came to Nanning for a training course, he was
charged 150 yuan (18 U.S. dollars) and dropped half-way. Zhang's
accident and people's complaints shocked the Nanning policymakers,
who soon worked out a series of measures to regulate the city's
taxi business.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the new measures, fare charges and meters are
regularly checked by the local authorities and complaint
telephones are open to the public.
</P>
<P>
Those who are found refusing a fare or overcharging three times
will have their licenses revoked, according to local authorities.
</P>
<P>
Drivers are required to wear uniforms while on duty. And
serving passengers politely and wholeheartedly is coming into
vogue among Nanning taxi drivers.
</P>
<P>
To offer more convenience for travelers the city map, timetable
of trains, buses and planes, and frequently used telephone numbers
are available in each taxi. Servicemen and their relatives also
receive a 20 percent discount on taxi fares.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, to serve passengers better, Nanning's taxi
drivers contributed to social security undertakings. They made
donations to flood victims and sent four color TVs to People's
Liberation Army soldiers stationed in frontier garrisons.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to Zhang Shan's mistreatment, a letter of thanks
from Beijing on Aug. 17 told of a good deed by a Nanning taxi
driver.
</P>
<P>
One day in June a taxi driver named Liao Qi sent two Beijing
visitors to the airport. He later found a black bag with 230,000
yuan in his car. When he rushed the bag to the two people who were
boarding, they were moved to tears.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in recent years the city's taxi drivers
collected 2.16 million yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0240 </DOCNO>
