<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, March 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan said today
that the good momentum of Sino-U.S. is accompanied by good
opportunities for further improvement and development.
</P>
<P>
Tang made the remark today during a meeting with Acting
Undersecretary of State John Holum, who arrived in Beijing for a
series of regular sub-cabinet level discussions covering
wide-ranging areas, including political, military, security and
arms control issues.
</P>
<P>
Tang stressed that maintaining and developing healthy and
stable Sino-U.S. relations protects the fundamental interests of
both nations.
</P>
<P>
He said China and the United States are finalizing detailed
preparations for the forthcoming state visit by President Bill
Clinton. (China-US-Discussions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Foreign ministers of the six-nation Contact Group met
Wednesday in Bonn trying to seek new approaches to end the
conflict in the southern Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
According to diplomatic sources in Bonn, the meeting has a main
objective to urge the federal Yugoslav leadership, not just
Serbia, to begin a political dialogue with Kosovo Albanians on the
future status of the troubled region.
</P>
<P>
However, the talks have been overshadowed by difference in
opinions among the Contact Group members consisting of Britain,
France, Germany, Italy, Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
While U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright proposes to
tighten sanctions on Belgrade, most other group members is said to
favor "maintaining pressure" on Belgrade to enter
talks. (Bonn-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Commission has recommended 11 European
Union member states for the founding of the European single
currency.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation was made during a special meeting of the
European Parliament, to which the commission, the executive body
of the 15-nation union, presented its report on economic
convergence.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, Germany, Spain, France, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg,
the Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and Finland were recommended as
having met the necessary conditions to adopt the single currency,
the Euro, on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Britain, serving the six-month rotating presidency of the
union, and Denmark exercised their right under the Maastricht
Treaty to opt out of the first wave for the Economic and Monetary
Union (EMU) while Greece and Sweden were judged by the commission
not economically ready to join. (EU-Euro)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW - Russian Acting Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko said
Wednesday that Russia will not follow OPEC's suggestion to cut
daily oil production by 13,700 tons in effort to boost prices.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with The Sevodnya newspaper, the former energy
minister stressed that production cutbacks would be dangerous for
Russia's oil infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
"Most oil wells in Russia are aged, and if they are temporarily
closed, 30 percent of them will never operate again," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government will be unable to compensate for
losses resulting from restrictions on oil production, he added.
(Russia-Oil Output-Cut)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- The People's Bank of China (PBOC), the nation's
central bank, lowered interest rates on bank loans and deposits on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the central bank initiated reform of the deposit
reserve fund system on March 21, and plans to reduce interest
rates on loans and deposits granted to financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The new steps represent important and effective measures the
new government has adopted for economic reform.
</P>
<P>
Economists contend that the fourth round of interest rate
reductions since 1996 will provide a sound macroeconomic
environment for the nation's economic growth. (China-Interest Rate
Reduction-Economy) 
</P>
</TEXT>
