<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investments Soar in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Investments registered at the
Philippine Board of Investments (BOI) reached 79.1 billion pesos
(2.1 billion U.S. dollars) in the first two months this year, up
by 65 percent compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Star Thursday quoted BOI Managing Director
Melito Salazar as saying that the board approved 56 new or
expansion projects with the amount of investments.
</P>
<P>
Salazar said the number of projects actually went down but some
of them are big-ticket ventures mainly in power generation and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Out of the aggregate investment commitments, almost 24 percent
were invested into the country as equity, of which 61 percent were
foreign investments, he added.
</P>
<P>
The biggest source of foreign investments during the period was
China's Hong Kong, with 6.42 billion pesos (173 million dollars).
It was followed by Japan and Britain.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the BOI approved a total investment of 554.6 billion
pesos (15 billion dollars), up 40 percent from 1996. However, most
of the investments were from domestic investors as foreign
investments declined by 18 percent to 1.053 billion dollars only.
</P>
</TEXT>
