<HEADLINE> Zambia's Foreign Debt Increases by 12.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official
disclosed here Wednesday that Zambia's foreign debt increased by
12.5 percent to 7.2 billion Dollars in 1997 from 6.4 billion in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question at parliament as to where Zambia's
foreign debt stands, Finance Minister Edith Nawakwi attributed
the increase in the foreign debt to continued borrowing instead
of arrears, Zambia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Zambia owes the Paris Club members 2.5 billion Dollars and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) 1.2 billion Dollars, she
explained.
</P>
<P>
The government paid 125 million Dollars last year toward the
serving of the country's foreign debt, the minister said, adding
that the debt servicing will continue so as to enhance national
development.
</P>
<P>
However, the newly-appointed finance minister who replaced
Renald Penza last week stressed that the Zambian government is
committed to the reduction of the country's debt burden and
called for support from all stake-holders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
