<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Post Office Still on Sell-Off Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 25 (Xinhua) - Post Office privatization has not
been ruled out by the British government despite earlier
statements that it was not on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Neville Bain, new chairman, was quoted Wednesday as saying that
all options were being considered in the review into the future of
the business.
</P>
<P>
The chairman was speaking after announcing an extension of the
price freeze on first and second-class stamps for at least another
year and expressing concern about delays in completing the review.
</P>
<P>
Postage rates were last increased in 1996, when 1p was added to
both first and second-class stamps, making them 26p and 20p
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Bain said prices could be kept down because the organization
was now more efficient. He said the amount of business done by
Royal Mail was growing and the Post Office was on target to meet
this year's government demands for cash.
</P>
<P>
But the chairman gave warning that the Post Office faced a
critical time against international competitors and needed the
Government to finish a long-running review into giving the
organisation more commercial freedom quickly.
</P>
<P>
the commercial freedom means the Post Office could be
privatized, but Bain said: "I believe it more likely that some
other form of commercial freedom will go forward."
</P>
<P>
He said: "If we are to maintain our position as market leader
we need the freedom to behave commercially, to raise capital to
invest even more, develop new services and move into new markets."
</P>
<P>
However, the Treasury has asked the Post Office to provide
almost 1 billion pounds (1.63 billion US dollars) for the
Exchequer over the next three financial years.
</P>
<P>
Bain said profitability and cash generation would be damaged if
the contribution to the Treasury, currently 75p to 90p of post-tax
profits, stayed at these levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
