<HEADLINE> French Rightwing Politician Plans to Set Up New Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The President of the French
center-rightwing Democratic Force (FD) party, Francois Bayrou,
Wednesday announced that he will set up a new center-right party
to replace the Union for French Democracy (UDF), the twin party of
the Gaullist Rally for the Republic.
</P>
<P>
The FD is an affiliate party of the UDF, which is crumbling
apart after five of its regional leaders allied with the far-right
National Front (FN) in the regional elections.
</P>
<P>
"UDF lacks cohesion. It lacks authority. It appears to
hesitate over essential issues. This situation cannot continue,"
Bayrou told the press.
</P>
<P>
He said that the envisaged new party will rally all the
center-right forces while rejecting the far-right.
</P>
<P>
"The French democracy needs a strong, large, united and
responsible party, on the space of center and center-right," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came when Alain Madelin, the President of
another center-right party the Liberal Democratic Party, which is
also an affiliate party of the UDF, is facing the cracking up of
his party because of dispute within the party over whether to ally
with the FN. 
</P>
</TEXT>
