<HEADLINE> PNA Urges U.S. to Announce its Peace Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) has called on the United States to move faster in
announcing its latest initiative aimed at breaking the deadlocked
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Media and Communication Center (JMCC), a
Palestinian information center based in East Jerusalem, Wednesday
quoted a statement of PNA President Yasser Arafat's Advisor Nabil
Abu Rodaineh as saying that the PNA hoped that the U.S.-proposed
peace initiative calling for a 13 percent Israeli troop
redeployment in the West Bank could be announced soon.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. withheld its announcement of the peace proposal after
it was rejected by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Nabil stressed that any initiative must be accompanied by
guarantees of a halt to settlement activities, redeployment and
implementation of the signed agreements between Israel and the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The PNA issued the call before U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross's
return to the region on Thursday. Ross was scheduled to hold talks
with Arafat on Thursday in Ramallah, West Bank, shortly after his
arrival.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. reportedly said that it would announce its initiative
after President Bill Clinton's return from his current African
trip.
</P>
<P>
It has promised to allow Israel to have some more time to
make its decision on the percentage of troop redeployment in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ross said earlier in Washington that his current trip to the
Middle East was "critical."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Israel's rejection of the U.S. proposal, PNA
Higher Education Minister Hanan Ashrawi told the JMCC on
Wednesday that this was an example of Israeli intransigence
toward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
She said that the PNA would deal favorably with any party
wishing to advance the peace process, referring to the European
Union's desire for a larger role in the process.
</P>
<P>
The EU's role was complimentary rather than in competition to
the U.S. role, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
