<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contact Group Raises Pressure on Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Without imposing new sanctions,
foreign ministers of the six-nation Contact Group on Wednesday
issued a sort of ultimatum on Belgrade forcing it to agree to
begin a dialogue with Kosovo Albanians within four weeks, or
to face punitive measures.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after a meeting in Bonn, foreign
ministers of Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Russia and the
United States, which comprise the Contact Group, said they had
decided to maintain and implement the punitive measures agreed at
an earlier meeting in London on March 9 if Belgrade failed to
comply with the demands made then.
</P>
<P>
In London, the Contact Group demanded that President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia publicly agree to a number of step:
political negotiations with the Kosovo Albanians, removal of the
Serbian special police from Kosovo and full access to the area for
aid and human rights organizations.
</P>
<P>
Although the Contact Group determined on Wednesday that some
progress had been made by Belgrade, it also noted what had been
done was not enough.
</P>
<P>
In order to increase the pressure on Belgrade, the group
members announced that they would seek adoption of an arms embargo
against Belgrade by the UN Security Council by March 31.
</P>
<P>
They also decided to meet again in four weeks to reassess the
situation.
</P>
<P>
"If President Milosevic takes the steps specified in London, we
will reconsider existing measures including action in the Security
Council to terminate the arms embargo. If Belgrade fails to meet
the London benchmarks,....we shall take steps to apply further
measures as announced in London," the Contact Group said in its
statement.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference after the meeting, U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright said: "We are moving gradually, but
unmistakably forward in the direction of greater pressure against
Belgrade. The only way out for President Milosevic is through
meaningful dialogue with the Kosovo Albanian community."
</P>
<P>
However, she also admitted the difference of opinions among the
Contact Group members. In the view of the United States, it would
be justified in imposing even tougher measures given the renewed
fightings in Kosovo recently, she said.
</P>
<P>
Sounding a different view, Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeni
Primakov told reporters that progress should not depend
exclusively on Belgrade, it should also depend on the Kosovo
Albanian side.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group on Wednesday also condemned terrorist actions
in Kosovo and urged all leaders of the Kosovo Albanians to declare
clear opposition to violence and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The group also made clear that it supported neither
independence of Kosovo nor the maintenance of the status quo. "We
support a substantially greater degree of autonomy for Kosovo
which must include meaningful self-administration," the statement
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Hopes to Strengthen Ties With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano said Wednesday that the aim of his official visit to
Beijing starting March 30 is to build up closer relations with
China.
</P>
<P>
"We will reaffirm our hope that the economic relationship can
be as good as the political one between the two countries," said
President Chissano in an interview with Xinhua in his office
here.
</P>
<P>
The president added that the political ties between the two
nations have been good and stable and that there has never been
any setback in them.
</P>
<P>
There was once a downturn in the economic cooperation for
quite a long period, and both countries hope this cooperation
will be restored and improved, he said.
</P>
<P>
President Chissano said during the visit he will brief Chinese
leaders on the political, economic and social situations in
Mozambique, and "we will do our best to strengthen cooperation
with China in various fields, such as science, technology, trade
and culture."
</P>
<P>
"We are interested in Chinese approaches of economic reforms
and its opening up to the outside world," said Chissano.
</P>
<P>
He said he will invite more Chinese businessmen to invest in
Mozambique, adding that recently, more and more Chinese
entrepreneurs came to investigate in Mozambique and became
interested in investing in this southern African country.
</P>
<P>
"The future is bright for our cooperation. And we will work to
restore the intergovernmental mixed committee and try to seal
some agreements, especially in the field of investment promotion
and protection," said Chissano.
</P>
<P>
He reminded that when he met Deng Xiaoping in Beijing on May
18, 1988, the late Chinese leader told him that "poverty is not
socialism."
</P>
<P>
He told this correspondent that he "fully agreed with Mr. Deng
on this saying."
</P>
<P>
President Chissano left Maputo on Wednesday afternoon for a
two-day visit to Singapore. He will pay an official visit to
China from March 30 to April 3, and afterwards he will go to
Macao for a two-day trip.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the Mozambican president will be accompanied
by his wife Marrelina, Minister of Foreign Affairs and
Cooperation Leonardo Simao, Minister of Planning and Finance
Tomas Salomao, Minister of Industry, Trade and Tourism Oldemiro
Baloi and Minister of Public Works and Housing Roberto White.
</P>
</TEXT>
