<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Satisfied over Oil Reduction Move by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Minister of Petroleum
Albina Assis Wednesday expressed satisfaction over some
countries' decision to cut oil production so as to restore
petroleum price to the previous level on the international
market.
</P>
<P>
She made the statement to the press here in the airport on
returning from a member and non member meeting of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) in Monaco.
However, she did not reveal whether Angola would reduce oil
production or not.
</P>
<P>
Recently, crude oil prices on the international market had
plunged from 19 Dollars a barrel to 12 Dollars, thus striking
panic in some oil-producing and exporting countries.
</P>
<P>
At the Monaco meeting, Albina said, countries such as Saudi
Arabia, Guatemala and Mexico agreed to cut their oil output,
which is unprecedented in the history.
</P>
<P>
She referred to their decision as a "positive sign," which
might lead to the restoration of oil prices to the normal level
on the international market.
</P>
<P>
Angola, a country rich in oil reserves, has a daily oil
production of 750,000 barrels, which has made it the second
largest oil-producing country in sub-Saharan Africa, second only
to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The fluctuation of oil price on the international market would
surely affect the Angolan economy which relies heavily on oil
production and export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
