<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Banks Lend Billions of Rand for Blacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 25 (Xinhua) -- South African banks
facilitated 8.2 billion Rand (1.64 million U.S. Dollars) worth of
black empowerment transactions in 1997, the Banking Council of
South Africa (COSAB) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing its operations for the past year, COSAB said its
drive to facilitate the empowerment process was being hampered by
a lack of adequate information on the country's informal sector.
</P>
<P>
More would have to be done to finance the more than 30 percent
of the population that is without employment, it said.
</P>
<P>
"Informal businesses that do not have permanent addresses or
minimum capital bases are not bankable and the role of banks in
such circumstances is to develop ways in which they might assist
non-governmental organizations to supply funding and services to
such businesses satisfactorily," the review said.
</P>
<P>
The review expressed concern at a growing culture on
non-payment of loans to facilitate the transformation process.
</P>
<P>
The culture of defaulting was most evident in the housing
sector, where 250,000 loans worth 11 billion Rand (220 million
Dollars) were made in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Non payment has led to the repossession of 18,200 township
houses on which mortgage loans of 770 million Rand (154 million
Dollars) are owing," the review said.
</P>
<P>
The general economic slowdown for most of 1997 resulted in
high levels of unemployment and retrenchments in South Africa as
most companies embarked on cost cutting measures to retain
profitability. This, in turn, led to a surge in defaults, local
observers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
