<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Announces Further Power Rationing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Ghana, gripped by one of its worst
energy crisis since independence, announced further power
rationing measures Wednesday, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
An announcement by the Electricity Corporation of Ghana (ECG)
said that henceforth, power would be supplied for 12 hours in
every 36 hours as against 12 hours in every 24 hours previously.
</P>
<P>
Accra, the capital, has been divided into three parts for the
exercise and power cuts and supplies will rotate among them.
</P>
<P>
As a result, at any one time, two-thirds of Accra's 1.7
million residents will be without electricity.
</P>
<P>
Drought, possibly linked to El Nino, has cut the flow of water
to Ghana's main 912 megawatt Akosombo hydro-power plant and an
explosion at the Takoradi thermal plant last week compounded the
problems by shutting down one of the two 100 megawatt generators
there.
</P>
<P>
Repairs are expected to take at least a month.
</P>
<P>
Power rationing in Ghana began on January 10. At first, supply
was cut by 30 percent, later by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Akosombo currently generates only 300 megawatts. To conserve
water, three of the station's six turbines have been closed down,
while the remaining three run at 70 percent of their capacity.
</P>
<P>
Akosombo plant manager, Francis Arkerst, said Monday that the
level of water at the dam is now 239.34 feet. The lowest level
ever recorded since the dam was built 32 years ago was 235.6 feet
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to be able to continue running three generators until
the end of June, when normally the lake level starts rising again
as a result of rains," said Arkerst. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
