<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanians to Have More Fish at Table </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The consumption of fish
per capita in Tanzania is expected to rise to 20 kilograms
annually, up from the present level of 12 kilograms, according to
a seminar held here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Professor Philip Bwathondi, director general of the Tanzania
Fisheries Research Institute, told the seminar that the east
African country has a large potential to tap since it has vast
water areas.
</P>
<P>
As a coastal country, Tanzania has abundant marine resources
in the Indian Ocean, such as cuttlefishes, crabs, prawns and
oysters, among others, Bwathondi said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tanzania boasts of large water space in Lake
Victoria, the second-largest freshwater lake in the world, as
well as the Tanganyika Lake, the Nyasa Lake, and several rivers.
</P>
<P>
However, little attempt has been made to fish due to lack of
strategies, technology and financial support, said W. Haule,
fisheries officer in Fisheries Department.
</P>
<P>
"The country's fishing remains at an extensive level," Haule
told some 20 participants at the seminar, organized by the
Wildlife Conservation Society of Tanzania to discuss the
country's aquiculture prospect.
</P>
<P>
To increase production, Professor Bwathondi has appealed to
the government to work out scientific strategies and intensify
researches on fish farming.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the training of farmers and development of
small-scale ponds in the rural areas to breed freshwater fish.
</P>
</TEXT>
