<HEADLINE> AL Calls for Resuming Talks on All Peace Tracks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League Council has urged
all parties concerned to intensify efforts to get Israel to abide
by all relevant international resolutions and resume talks on all
peace tracks, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Council, at its 109th session Wednesday, stressed the
necessity of spurning all attempts meant to prematurely jump to
the final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The session, held at the foreign ministerial level calls for
continuing Arab contacts with world countries and the U.N. to
forge a unified stance enabling Palestine to be a U.N. member.
</P>
<P>
The conferees voiced appreciation of Europe's peace role,
calling for further vitaminizing this role so that it can thrust
the peace process out of its blind alley.
</P>
<P>
A statement, issued at the Council's 109th session, spelled out
Arab concern over the serious crisis in the peace drive as a
result of the policies and stances adopted by the incumbent
Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
It also issued a warning that the destruction of the peace
process would only spawn a fresh cycle of tension in the Mideast,
for which Israel alone would bear full responsibility.
</P>
<P>
"No comprehensive and just peace could be established unless
Israel withdraw from Palestinian, Syrian and Lebanese
territories," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Arab foreign ministers condemned Israel's misleading media
campaigns on a possible pullout from south Lebanon on Israeli
security terms, which the statement said, were a breach of the
clearly-worded U.N. Resolution 425 calling for the unconditional
Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The ministers stressed the inseparability of the Syrian and
Lebanese tracks and made clear that the realization of just and
comprehensive peace in the Mideast was the only guarantee for
providing security to the region.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, which focused on the Arab-Israeli
conflicts and the Mideast peace process, began Tuesday and was
attended by foreign ministers of 16 Arab countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
