<HEADLINE> Refugees in Tanzania in Acute Shortage of Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Official from the United
Nations High Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) said Wednesday that
refugees in west Tanzania's Kigoma Region are facing acute
shortage of food.
</P>
<P>
"Although the impact varies from one camp to another, food
shortages are generally at alarmingly low levels," UNHCR Senior
External Relations Officer Vincent Parker told reporters here in
the capital.
</P>
<P>
Destruction of roads and other infrastructure by floods blamed
on the El Nino weather phenomenon has severely affected the
delivery of food to refugee camps, the official said.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the use of trains for the movement of
Congolese refugees from the Lugufu Camp has been temporarily
suspended due to damages of rail tracks.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR, however, has resorted to the use of trucks despite
difficulties, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
By March 23, a total of 29,622 refugees had been assisted to
be repatriated in an organized manner from Tanzania to Uvira and
Baraka in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
About 74,000 Congolese refugees, who fled a civil war in the
Democratic Republic of Congo that brought Laurent Kabila to power
in the former Zaire last May, lived in western Tanzanian camps
before a voluntary repatriation program began last September.
</P>
<P>
Three boats, each carrying 2,000 Congolese refugees, have been
arranged since March 16 so as to speed up the repatriation
process. The repatriation exercise is expected to be completed by
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program (WFP) Country Director, Irene M. Lacy,
elaborated after the press conference that food warehouses in
refugee camps have a very low capacity for cereals and pulses and
there is little hope of building new warehouses until the
rehabilitation of the railway from Dar es Salaam to Dodoma.
</P>
<P>
Despite transportation problems, she said, the WFP continues
to deliver food supplies on a daily basis and food distribution
situation has improved slightly this week.
</P>
<P>
"I am optimistic that minimum rations to all refugees can be
maintained during the coming weeks," Lacy noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
