<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Bans Corporal Punishment to Pupils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Britain's parliament voted on
Wednesday 211 to 15 to ban corporal punishment in all schools.
</P>
<P>
The previous Conservative government outlawed corporal
punishment in state schools in 1986, but teachers in the estimated
200 fee-paying schools can still beat misbehaving pupils as
punishment.
</P>
<P>
Liberal Democrat legislator Don Foster, who proposed the
amendment to the government education bill, said the ban was
"unfinished business" and pointed out that no other country in
Europe allowed corporal punishment of children.
</P>
<P>
Corporal punishment has for centuries been an integral part of
the upbringing of many children, particularly boys.
</P>
<P>
The Independent Schools Council (ISC) -- which represents 1,300
schools and covers 80 percent of children attending private
schools in Britain -- said its members had already stopped caning
pupils.
</P>
<P>
"Many schools concluded, long before any form of legal ban was
contemplated, that corporal punishment impeded good education,"
ISC chairman Ian Beer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Britain abolished whipping as a form of judicial punishment in
1948 and flogging in the navy in 1957. Corporal punishment in
prison and reformatory institutions ended in 1967. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
