<HEADLINE> EU Mission Visits Ethiopia to Boost Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Visiting European Parliament
delegation Wednesday held talks here with their Ethiopian
colleagues led by Speaker of the House of People's
Representatives Dawit Yohannes on bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, Glenys Kinnock, head
of the European Parliament delegation, said she was impressed
with Ethiopia's effort to exploit the country's potential to
alter the very poorest social and economic indicators.
</P>
<P>
She also expressed the Parliament's concern over maintaining
the Lome IV Convention which has been the basis for partnership
among the African, Caribbean and Pacific group-European Union
(ACP-EU) countries.
</P>
<P>
Kinnock refuted the argument which says the Lome IV Convention
is out of date and has no relevance, stressing that it has a role
not only in terms of aid but also in facilitating the trade
partnership among the private sectors of member nations of the
convention.
</P>
<P>
Speaker Dawit said on his part that the Lome IV Convention has
been quite significant in the relationship between African
countries and Europe.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to see the renegotiation of the Lome
Convention," he added.
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament delegation arrived here Tuesday for a
five-day working visit to Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The Lome IV Convention, which currently governs ACP-EU
relations, is due to expire at the beginning of the year 2000.
ACP and EU countries are expected to reach a new cooperative
agreement between them in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
