<HEADLINE> Greek Foreign Minister Sees no Greek-Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Greek Foreign
Minister Theodoros Pangalos said here on Wednesday fears expressed
by some U.S. officials that the Kosovo crisis could lead to war
between Greece and Turkey are just "rubbish."
</P>
<P>
Pangalos made the remarks when speaking to reporters at the end
of a five-day visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Greece and Turkey have common interests in this region,"
Pangalos said. "I think on the contrary that this is an
opportunity for Greek-Turkish cooperation, including military
cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. officials feared that Serbia's crackdown on Albanian
separatists in its Kosovo province could cause a conflict between
Greece and Turkey, who both are the members of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
The fear is based on assumptions that Greece might side with
its fellow Orthodox Serbians, while Turkey could support the
Muslim Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The Greek foreign minister said that could only happen "if
Turkey rediscovers the dream of becoming the new Ottoman empire"
in which Turkey ruled much of the Balkans and the Middle East
before World War I.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think anybody in Ankara is crazy enough to say that,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Pangalos did not rule out that the Kosovo crisis might
spill across borders, saying it could affect Macedonia, which
also has many Albanians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
