<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemen to Cut Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Yemen has decided to cut its oil
production of 380,000 barrels per day (bpd) by 2 to 3 percent as
from April 1, the Yemeni Ministry of Oil and Mineral Resources
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken in response to the current efforts made
by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) and
non-OPEC oil producers to stabilize oil prices in the world
markets, a ministry official told the Yemeni news agency Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official said Yemen believed that the increase in oil
production was the prime cause of the drop in oil prices.
He expressed the hope that the oil producing countries would not
engage in a race of raising production.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and Venezuela, OPEC members, as well as non-OPEC
Mexico announced on Sunday a total reduction of 1.1 million
barrels per day of their oil production starting in April
to save the sagging prices, which has plunged to 10 dollars a
barrel, the lowest in nine years.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Iran, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates also
announced to cut their oil productions.
</P>
<P>
OPEC members decided last December to raise their oil production
ceiling from 25.03 million barrels a day to 27.05 million, causing
a drop in prices due to decreasing demand, a mild winter in
northern hemisphere and the Asian financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
