<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Jordan's Tourist Season Spoiled by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's tourism industry, a
leading hard currency earner, has fallen prey to the recent
unstable situation in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Semi-official Jordan Times daily Wednesday reported that
tourist industrialists have complained of a late and sluggish start
of the current tourist season which usually starts in mid-February
and runs through May.
</P>
<P>
No official figures to indicate the current awkward tourist
situation are available, but a poor performance appears to be all
too clear.
</P>
<P>
Dakkak Tours and Travel, one of the leading travel agencies in
Jordan, has reported a cancellation of 15 to 20 percent of groups
booked for February.
</P>
<P>
Many tourist managers and agents were quoted in the newspaper
as saying that their business has been withering since the
beginning of this year. But they declined to disclose details like
the number of tourists they are losing.
</P>
<P>
With no customers coming, few of the 240 tourist buses running
between Amman and the country's leading attraction, the Petra, or
the ancient Nabataean Kingdom's capital some 2,500 years ago, are
now maintaining their daily service.
</P>
<P>
The country's leading Jordan Express Tourist Transport (JETT)
was the last to stop its Amman-Petra operation nearly two weeks
ago, saying the service became "financially unfeasible." Another
Alpha Company has stopped daily tours from Amman to all the
locations in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Tourism agencies attributed the tension in the region as the
key reason for the inactive performance, pointing out to facts
like the terrorist massacre of 67 tourists in Luxor, Egypt, last
November and the instable security situation in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The standoff between the United Nations and Iraq over weapons
inspection coupled with the U.S. military threat is another key
factor used to explain the sagging market.
</P>
<P>
"If this (the standoff) had not happened, this would have been
our best season," Grace Qassis, Sales and Marketing Manager at the
International Traders Company, told Jordan Times.
</P>
<P>
Tourism agencies are losing their conventional major part of
clients -- people from the Middle East countries, who would rather
like to stay home in fear of the regional tension, agents said.
</P>
<P>
The second major part of tourists coming to Jordan were those
from Europe and the United States for regional package tour that
includes Jordan, Israel and Egypt. Agents reported that the
U.S. market has been the hardest-hit, saying it proved to be the
most sensitive to regional instability.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is the third largest industry for the kingdom, earning
the country some 600 million U.S. dollars a year, or 10 percent of
the gross domestic products.
</P>
<P>
The industry has experienced ups and downs during the past few
years on the impact of the regional security situation.
</P>
<P>
The 1990-1991 Gulf crisis almost ravaged the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
But the sector benefited most from the peace treaty reached
with Israel in 1994. A following bilateral tourism agreement
played a big role in bringing a boom to the industry.
</P>
<P>
However, after the hard-line Likud group took over the Israeli
government in mid-1996, the Israeli-Palestinian conflicts were
accelerated and upgraded. The tension had a negative effect on
Jordan's tourism industry, triggering a downward trend which lasts
till now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM: Peace Agreement Possible After Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri said Wednesday that Lebanon and Syria will be able to sign
peace agreements with Israel in three months if it withdraws from
occupied south Lebanon and Syria's Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Hariri made the remarks during a lunch with a visiting German
delegation head by Gerhard Schroeder, the president of German's
Federal Council.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated Lebanon's rejection of Israel's conditioned
withdrawal proposal, saying that Beirut cannon provide Israel
with any security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
Israel is promoting an international campaign to sell its
proposal to withdraw from south Lebanon on condition that the
Lebanese government agrees to guarantee the security of Israeli
northern border.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said that the Lebanese government will be accountable
only to its people and parliament and cannot be accountable to
Israel. "This is the difference between what we say and what
Israel says," he added.
</P>
<P>
"I have announced for several times that Lebanon and Syria are
ready to sign a peace agreement with Israel in three months if
Israel shows interest in withdrawing from Golan Heights to the
border on June 4, 1967 and from all Lebanese territory," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But, if Israel doesn't want to make peace, we will continue
asking everybody to push Israel toward the peace process," the
prime minister added.
</P>
<P>
Hariri stressed that as long as the peace agreement is not
reached between the two countries, Israel cannot ask Lebanon to
give it security guarantees, adding that only under a peace
agreement will Lebanon cooperate with Israel in many fields,
including security.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer area in
south Lebanon since it declared the area as a "security zone" in
1985 to allegedly protect its northern villages and towns from
Lebanese guerrillas cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it has been occupying Syria's Golan Heights captured
during the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria have vowed to put their negotiations with
Israel on the same track, and therefore considered the current
Israeli conditional withdrawal proposal from Lebanon as a "plot" to
drive a wedge between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
