<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy, Israeli Minister to Meet in Miami, U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. special envoy Dennis Ross
is going to hold a meeting with Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai on Wednesday in U.S. southern city of Miami on the
possible revitalization of the stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the two men are to discuss U.S. ideas on the scale
of pull-out of the Israeli troops from the West Bank and Israeli
proposals on a withdrawal from its occupied zone in South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Ross said it was a chance for the United States and Israel to
talk about their views on the peace process in the region.
</P>
<P>
"The minister will obviously have his views. We'll see what
happens," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ross will fly to the Middle East after his meeting with
Mordechai in Miami in a hope to revive the peace process which has
been blocked for over a year.
</P>
<P>
"There has to be a point at which we can draw to a
conclusion. The president and secretary (of state) have sent me
out there to vitalize our ideas. At some point, we'll make a
judgment on whether we've done all that we can or not," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has suggested Israel withdraw from 13.1
percent of land from the West Bank with three months in three
phases while the Palestinians meet the security requirement from
Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has rejected the U.S. proposal, saying it could
only afford to cede 9 percent of the land on the West Bank on
consideration of its security.
</P>
<P>
Asked if this was a last chance for the Israeli-Palestinian
peace process, Mordechai said: "Never say last chance. All the
time, we'll have another chance. We'll go chance by chance."
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said he and Ross would also discuss Israeli
proposals on South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel has proposed withdrawal of its troops from its
occupied zone in South Lebanon if the Beirut government
guarantees security from cross-border guerrilla raids.
</P>
<P>
But Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik al-Hariri on Wednesday
threw cold water on the proposal, saying Lebanon could not be
accountable to Israel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
