<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Inspector Lauds Iraq's Spirit of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 25 (Xinhua) -- U.N. chief arms inspector Richard
Butler said here on Wednesday that he is satisfied with the spirit
of cooperation shown by Iraqi officials during their talks in the
past two days.
</P>
<P>
There was "a new spirit, a level of cooperation not only
outdoors (during weapons inspections), but also indoors where we
settle the policy of technical matters," Butler told a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Butler is the chairman of the United Nations Special Commission
(UNSCOM) charged with eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM must certify that Iraq has destroyed the lethal
weapons before the U.N. can lift the economic sanctions imposed on
Iraq in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
"If Iraq continues to show the degree of cooperation that now
seems to be evident, then I am optimistic during this calendar
year, we will make significant advance toward the end of the
disarmament phase in missile and chemical fields," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under relevant U.N. resolutions, there will be a transition to
on-going monitoring phase following the present disarmament phase,
Butler said.
</P>
<P>
But so far, none of Iraq's file is qualified to enter into the
monitoring phase, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The missile file is going to be looking very close, relatively
soon; chemical file not far behind it; and as I said before, the
biological file is not in a good shape, hopefully, the meeting
which is under way in Vienna will give it a leap forward," Butler
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official, who arrived here on Sunday for a five-day
visit, said he and Iraqi officials have achieved "concrete and
practical things."
</P>
<P>
Butler and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz held three
rounds of talks on Monday and Tuesday to discuss the results of
the technical evaluation meetings held in early February on
missile warheads and chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
They have agreed that further technical meetings would be held
to iron out differences between Iraq and the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
Butler said that Aziz has expressed the confidence that they
would be able to continue their work with Iraq's cooperation in
the future.
</P>
<P>
He said he will submit a report to the U.N. Security Council on
April 11 and that it will be as "technical and scientific" as
possible.
</P>
<P>
The report will not only show some of the difficulties in the
weapons inspection process, but "the progress we have experienced
in the past two days" as well, he said.
</P>
<P>
As the chief weapons inspector, Butler has the responsibility
to submit to the Security Council a report every six months about
the progress of Iraq's disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the inspections of Iraq's eight presidential sites,
Butler said that will start "very, very soon."
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure we will be able to do our work in a normal way,
consistent with those special procedures with both sides'
cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached between Iraq and the U.N., Iraq will
open its presidential sites, originally declared off-limits, to a
special group which comprises senior diplomats and UNSCOM experts.
</P>
<P>
According to well-informed diplomatic sources, the inspections
of the presidential compounds will take place on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
