<HEADLINE> Turkey Denounces Greece's Support for PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Turkey Wednesday accused Greece of
continuing its support for Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK), saying that Ankara will bring this issue to
international attention.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a regular news briefing here, Turkish Foreign
Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan said that an article published in
the latest issue of Time magazine has provided detailed proof on
the relationship between Athens and the PKK.
</P>
<P>
"Due to this relationship, Greece has violated international
agreements within the framework of the United Nations and the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE),"
Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
He added that these agreements have made it very clear that no
member country should be allowed to render support to any
terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government always terms the PKK, which has been
fighting for the autonomy in eastern and southeastern Turkey since
1984, as a terrorist organization.
</P>
<P>
The article published by Time magazine depicted a vivid picture
of the PKK activities in Greece, which has historically shared a
bitter relationship with neighboring Turkey.
</P>
<P>
This led to harsh reactions from Greek Foreign Minister
Theodoros Pangalos who was on a visit to Washington at that time.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the article named "A Hellenic Have", Utkan said that
"the terrorist fire of the PKK spreads virtually unchecked in
Greece."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the Turkish government would bring
this issue to some international bodies, such as the U.N. or the
OSCE, in order to prevent Athens' "unjust" action.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has always accused Greece of supporting the PKK,
saying that Greeks provide financial and military assistance to
the Kurdish militants. Athens, however, categorically denied the
charge.
</P>
<P>
More than 28,000 people have been killed since the PKK started
fighting for the establishment of an independent Kurdish state in
southeastern Turkey 14 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
