<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Debates Bill for Financing IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Wednesday
debated legislation providing nearly 18 billion U.S. dollars for
the International Monetary Fund (IMF), U.S. troops abroad and El
Nino damage at home.
</P>
<P>
But the House version of the legislation is prompting sharp
objections from Democrats, with Senate Democratic leader Tom
Daschle Wednesday calling a veto likely.
</P>
<P>
The Senate debated briefly an amendment by Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison, R-Texas, to set up conditions for a U.S. withdrawal of
troops from Bosnia, but she withdrew the amendment before a vote,
suggesting she just wanted to make a point.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the House Appropriations Committee approved two
separate bills. It used a voice vote to pass one with the IMF
money plus 505 million U.S. dollars to pay back dues owed the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The panel, by a party-line 29-21 roll call vote, passed another
measure with 2.9 billion U.S. dollars for the disasters and troops
in Bosnia and the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
To pay for the disaster measure, the committee approved 2.9
billion U.S. dollars in cuts to low-income housing, airport
projects, bilingual education and President Clinton's pet
Ameri-corps national service program. The Republican-proposed
reductions were approved in a 33-26 party-line vote.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Newt Gingrich defended the decision to cut
domestic programs, and responded to White House opposition by
questioning whether the Clinton administration wants a balanced
budget.
</P>
<P>
Daschle told reporters today that efforts in the House to try
to pay for the disaster aid and for military operations with
reductions in domestic programs was a "non starter."
</P>
<P>
He added that the president will be forced to veto the
legislation if it reaches his desk in such a form. 
</P>
</TEXT>
