<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Considers Emergency Meeting to Materialize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) was considering to hold an emergency
meeting to carry out a pact reached in Saudi Arabia to cut oil
supply to glutted markets, the group's chief said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
United Arab Emirates' (UAE) Minister of Petroleum and Mineral
Resources Obeid bin Saif Al Nasir, who was also President of OPEC,
said in a statement that "there are consultations among member
states to hold an emergency OPEC meeting to materialize Riyadh
pact."
</P>
<P>
The Riyadh pact was clinched by Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and
non-OPEC Mexico on Sunday with the aim of lowering world oil
production by 1.6 million to 2 million barrels per day (bpd) to
rescue oil prices which were depressed by oversupply and declining
demand.
</P>
<P>
The agreement had been able to increase oil prices by nearly 14
percent to over 15 U.S. dollars a barrel on Monday. But prices
fell back Tuesday by nearly 26 cents when traders paused for
breath to wait for the implementation of the pact.
</P>
<P>
The UAE minister did not specify the date of the possible
extraodinary OPEC meeting on carrying out the Riyadh accord, but
he said the issue would be discussed during a four-man market
monitoring committee of OPEC, which was expected to take place in
Vienna next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC market monitoring committee meeting scheduled to hold
last week was postponed to March 30 when OPEC said it needed "more
time to have a more in-depth view of the market situation, so as
to make appropriate recommendations to the conference."
</P>
<P>
Obeid said that OPEC members were also consulting to invite
some non-OPEC oil producers to next week's Vienna meeting. But he
did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The UAE oil minister Monday called on all world oil producing
countries -- both inside and outside OPEC -- to follow the sample
of Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico to reduce output to save
sagging oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen oil producing countries have been involved in the
current campaign to claw back oil supply and they have so far
agreed to cut output by 1.1 million bpds.
</P>
<P>
World oil prices began to collapse after OPEC decided in
November to raise its combined output ceiling by 10 percent to
27.5 million bpds from 25 million bpds.
</P>
<P>
The price crisis was compounded by Iraq's return to oil
markets and a decline in crude demand due to a mild winter in the
northern hemisphere and Asia's economic turmoil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Battery Recharge System A Boost for Electric Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 25 (Xinhua) -- A rapid battery recharge system,
developed by an international consortium of companies, will
greatly increase the efficiency of electric cars, the BBC radio
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Advanced Lead-Acid Battery Consortium, meeting in London
this week, claims that the new system could cut the time needed to
recharge conventional lead-acid batteries from hours to minutes.
</P>
<P>
One of the big technical obstacles to the success of electric
cars is that a run-down lead-acid battery can take up to twelve
hours to recharge.
</P>
<P>
It was impossible to recharge lead-acid batteries rapidly
because acid build-up near the plates could cause a rapid increase
in electrical resistance, which in turn caused overheating and the
risk of explosion.
</P>
<P>
The new system uses electronic control to prevent that.
Computers send charging currents up to 3,000 amps in pulses of a
tenth of a second, with an eight-millisecond gap to reduce
overheating.
</P>
<P>
Research by the consortium showed that traditional lead-acid
batteries can be recharged in only three minutes in this way.
</P>
<P>
The rapid recharge system also increases the battery life by 40
percent, the BBC said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Panel Passes Flag Desecration Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate's constitution
subcommittee on Wednesday approved a proposed constitutional
amendment that would ban flag burning.
</P>
<P>
Today's vote is the latest in a series of congressional
attempts to reverse the Supreme Court's 1989 ruling that
destroying the U.S. flag in protest is a form of constitutionally
protected speech.
</P>
<P>
A new constitutional amendment requires a two-thirds vote of
both houses of Congress, and of the legislatures in two-thirds of
the states. Previous flag amendments have passed the House of
Representatives, but fallen short of the necessary Senate
majority.
</P>
<P>
This year's resolution, which states that "Congress shall have
power to prohibit the physical desecration of the flag," has 61
co-sponsors -- six short of the two-thirds majority needed for
passage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
