<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Leaders Discuss Peace, Prosperity with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Six African leaders Wednesday
discussed ways for building a peaceful and prosperous Africa
with visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton at a summit in
Enteb, a lakeside city in central Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The summit, co-hosted by Clinton and Uganda President Yoweri
Museveni, was attended by presidents from Kenya, Tanzania,
Rwanda, the Democratic Republic of Congo, Ethiopian prime
minister and secretary general of the Organization of Africa
Unity.
</P>
<P>
It dwelt on speeding up the development of Africa's economy,
its integration into the global economy, and expanding Africa's
trade and investment opportunities, according to a declaration
issued after summit.
</P>
<P>
With reference to the creative and flexible examples from
post-war Europe and Asia, the summit pledged to form Africa's
strategies to facilitate Africa's global integration.
</P>
<P>
Based on the fact that regional intergration will create
greater market for African economies, the regional leaders
committed themselves to identifying the ways and means to
accelerate regional integration, which include international
dialogue aimed at economic reform, expansion of external resource
flows, increased investment in the infrastructure and building
African capacity, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Africa trade bill, according to the regional leaders, is a
major step forward for Africa's access to the U.S. market.
However, they added that African capacity to diversify economies
must be increased first, with the help of western technologies.
</P>
<P>
The African leaders welcome the decision of the U.S. Overseas
Private Investment Corporation (OPIC) which targets 500 million
Dollars for infrastructure investment in sub-Saharan Africa. They
pledged to take concrete measures aimed at promoting African
investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
In recognition of the African desire for increased
self-sufficiency and the dangers of aid dependency, the regional
leaders agree that an accelarated effort should be made to use
foreign assistance as a tool for the enhancement of trade,
investment and capital formation, as well as for sustainable
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and government also recognize the
continuing obstacle of debt burden to Africa's economic
transformation, and reaffirm their collective determination to
fully implement innovative approaches to the management and
lessening of the debt burden.
</P>
<P>
On the Great Lakes issue, the African leaders pledged to work
together to prohibit future atrocities to ensure peace and
stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The United States, in its turn, offered its commitment to
work with its African partners to stop atrocities and form long
term mechanism to prevent genocide in the future.
</P>
<P>
The destiny and security of Africa rest primarily in the hands
of Africans themselves, the statement noted. The leaders pledged
to seek a regional and African peace keeping capacity to settle
conflicts on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The leaders agree that stability in the region relies on the
sustainability of Africa democratization, and there is no fixed
model for democratic institutions or transformation.
</P>
<P>
After the summit, Clinton left here tonight for South Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
