<HEADLINE> Taliban Launch Major Offensive in Northern Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Islamic Taliban
militia launched a major infantry and jet assault on a strategic
town in northern Afghanistan and made some gains there, reports
reaching here Wednesday said.
</P>
<P>
Taliban fighters have launched three attacks on Pul-i-Khumri, a
major town in central Baghlan province, since late Tuesday, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Pul-i-Khumri lies midway along a key highway linking the north
of the country to the capital Kabul. It was defended by
anti-Taliban alliance forces of the Shiite Hezb-e-Wahdat faction
and northern warlord Rashid Dostum.
</P>
<P>
However, there were no details of casualties or damage from the
attacks, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban attack came after nearly two weeks of sporadic but
intense clashes between forces loyal to Dostum and the
Hezb-e-Wadhat in their northern city stronghold of Mazar-e-Sharif,
about 300 km north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia, who control around two-thirds of
Afghanistan including Kabul, have vowed to impose a strict Islamic
rule on a country gripped by 20 years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
The northern-based anti-Taliban alliance, which controls the
remaining one third, is dominated by ethnic-Tajik, Uzbek and
Hazara minorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
