<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plan for London Mayor Election Unveiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- British Deputy Prime Minister John
Prescott unveiled a plan on Wednesday for a directly elected mayor
of London as part of the plans to overhaul the way the British
capital is run.
</P>
<P>
Prescott told the parliament that the city would have
"radically new" type of government for London and have a
streamlined strategic authority.
</P>
<P>
"London needs leadership with a clear mandate from the people,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The mayor will form a "cabinet" and its work will be
scrutinized by an elected assembly of councillors.
</P>
<P>
Prescott said the proposals, to be put to a referendum on May
7, were an important part of the government's plans to
decentralize power. Up to five million Londoners will be able to
vote in the May ballot.
</P>
<P>
Former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher abolished the former
Greater London Council 11 years ago, dividing its work between
local authorities and other public bodies.
</P>
<P>
Many Londoners complain that the city lacks direction and needs
somebody powerful to coordinate its transport, environment and
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 100 Million Chinese Suffer from Hypertension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- One in every 13 Chinese suffers
from hypertension, or high blood pressure, the Chinese Ministry of
Health said in a report here today.
</P>
<P>
China now has some 110 million hypertension patients, as
against 90 million in 1991. Every year, about 3.2 million people
became hypertension patients in China, the report says.
</P>
<P>
"Due to ignorance and some unhealthy life styles, the disease
is imposing greater risks to the Chinese than ever," said
Wang Zhao, director of the ministry's Department of Disease
Control.
</P>
<P>
A national survey found that half of the Chinese people had
had their blood pressures measured. However, only 17 percent of
hypertension patients in cities and five percent in rural areas
took drugs regularly.
</P>
<P>
"We must let people know that healthy life styles and timely
treatment help control 75 percent of hypertension
cases," Wang said at a meeting that called upon supports from the
mass media in disease-control campaigns.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health has designated October 8 as the National
Hypertension Day so as to awaken the public's awareness of health
protection.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SEATINI to Hold Economic Workshop in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Southern and Eastern African
Trade, Information and Negotiations Initiative (SEATINI), in its
press statement, said that it will organize an economic workshop
from March 30 to April 4 here to analyze the phenomenon of
globalization.
</P>
<P>
The press statement said that the workshop would also analyze
the new trading regime under the World Trade Organization (WTO)
and consider a common framework of action at the WTO meeting in
Geneva in May this year.
</P>
<P>
Chief trade negotiators of 21 southern and eastern African
countries, and representatives from some non-governmental
organizations will participate in the workshop.
</P>
<P>
The press statement said that the world situation has changed
since end of the Cold War and African countries are facing with
special difficulties. They are ill-equipped to manage the new
process of globalization, it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development, 33 of the 48 least development countries are in
Africa, and their growth rates have lagged far behind those other
developing countries. Their share in the world trade has fallen
sharply from 1.7 percent in 1970 to 0.7 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The press statement said that there has been little structural
change in these countries and they continue to rely on a few
primary commodities for export earnings, adding that faced with
intensified competition, they are likely to face further erosion
of their share in the world market.
</P>
<P>
However, the press statement noted,
certain aspects of globalization are indeed very
positive even for the third world, such as the development and
spread of information technology.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of the workshop will feed into the process of the
ministerial conference of the Organisation of African Unity on
trade and development to be held from April 6 to April 9 in
Harare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Peace Conference Feared Scrapped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Somali ambassador to the Arab
League expressed fear Wednesday that the planned National
Reconciliation Conference of his country might not be held, the
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here on Wednesday, Abdullah Hassan
attributed the prospect to the lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the conference originally scheduled to
open in the Somali southwestern town of Baidoa on February 15 and
later postponed to March 31 needs 4 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Somali diplomat stopped short of blaming foreign parties
for the faltering of the conference.
</P>
<P>
"The Somalis, themselves, are shouldering the responsibility
for such failure," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hassan expressed hope that Arab League Secretary General Ahmed
Esmat Abdel-Meguid may visit Mogadishu, the Somali capital, to
get acquainted with the conditions.
</P>
<P>
His statement came two days after the leaders of the two most
powerful factions in Somalia assured that they were pursuing
arrangements for the conference in their separate letters to the
Arab League and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
It is believed to have aided the worry that the conference
might be canceled and clan conflicts renewed after Ali Mahdi
Mohamed and Hussein Fareh Aideed announced their decision on
February 14 to put off the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Mahdi is the leader of the Somali United Congress and Aideed
heads the Somali National Alliance.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement they signed last December, a federal
government will be formed at the National Reconciliation
Conference which will be attended by all factions in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Somalia has been hit heavily by factional wars since the ouster
of the late dictator Mohamed Siad Barre in 1991. More than 300,000
people have died in the war and ensuing famine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Buys Arms from 39 Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 25 (Xinhua) -- South Africa had imported
armaments from 39 countries in the past four years, Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki told parliament Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Between April 1, 1994 and February 9, 1998, South Africa
bought more than 104 million Rand (about 21 million U.S. dollars)
worth of arms from Spain and 81 million Rand (16 million dollars)
worth of arms from Israel, Mbeki said in a written reply to a
parliamentary question.
</P>
<P>
The country also bought, among others, 60 million Rand (12
million dollars) worth of armaments from Britain and 37 million
Rand (7.4 million dollars) worth of arms from France, South
African Press Association quoted Mbeki as saying.
</P>
<P>
The figures represented not only acquisitions for the national
defence force, but those by local industry for their own
products, Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa had exported weapons to 90 countries over this
period, including selling 637 million Rand (128 million dollars)
worth of weapons to India, he said.
</P>
<P>
The country also sold armaments worth 387 million Rand (78
million dollars) to Oman and weapons worth 339 million Rand (68
million dollars) to the United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Technology Will Change Business Face: Analysis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 25 (Xinhua) -- advances in electronic commerce,
networks and telecommunications will make businesses more
efficient and profitable as they head into the next century, a
leading U.S. consulting firm said.
</P>
<P>
In its Technology Forecast 1998 released on Wednesday, Price
Waterhouse highlights several technology trends:
</P>
<P>
- A rising number of "smart products" such as cars, phones and
home appliances that are accessed through networks and the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
Microprocessors may be installed in automobiles allowing repair
shops to diagnose problems via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
- Significant expansion of voice recognition capabilities in
devices such as phones that will reduce the need for
keyboards/touchpads.
</P>
<P>
Users will simply tell a computer to turn itself on, or use
their voice to have phones dial automatically.
</P>
<P>
- Increased use of satellite and wireless technologies by
companies reaching businesses and consumers.
</P>
<P>
The California-based Price Waterhouse said technology advances
may mean a large scale change for the cultural dynamics and
organizational processes of a "global corporation", and creation
of the potential for major improvements in productivity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
