<HEADLINE> U.S., Uganda Sign Investment Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. and Uganda signed an
Overseas Private Investors Cooperation (OPIC) agreement Wednesday
afternoon, enabling Ugandan investors get access to credit from
OPIC.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is a leeway for the Americans to invest in
Uganda and for any Ugandan investor who enters joint partnership
with American investors to access any amount of money to do
business.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Ugandan Finance Minister
Joash Mayanja Nkangi said the OPIC agreement will promote
business between Americans and Ugandans to a desirable scale. He
advised Ugandan businessmen to take the advantage of the credit
accessed by OPIC through the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by William Delay, the U.S.Secretary
for Commerce and a board member of OPIC, and the Ugandan finance
minister on behalf of their respective governments.
</P>
<P>
This is the first agreement signed between the two countreis
since U.S. President Bill Clinton came here for his two-day visit
to Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
