<HEADLINE> Southern Africa to Strengthen Quality Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 25 (xinhua) -- A senior Mozambican official in
charge of quality control said on Wednesday that Southern African
Development Community (SADC) countries will strengthen control on
quality of products made in the region.
</P>
<P>
Gabriela Da Silva, Director for national standardization and
quality control of Mozambique, told reporters on Wednesday that
representatives from SADC member states admitted that the quality
of the products made in Southern Africa is poor.
</P>
<P>
At a six-day Expert Conference on Standardization and Quality
Control in Southern Africa ended on Tuesday, the participants
discussed cooperation between the SADC countries in this field.
</P>
<P>
The representatives to the conference noted that the quality
of imports from other countries is bad. And they stressed that
efforts should be made to monitor and control the quality of both
the products manufactured in Southern African states and the
imported goods.
</P>
<P>
The best in quality control in the region is South Africa
where there are 1,500 enterprises registered passing quality
tests, they said.
</P>
<P>
Silver said that participants of the conference agreed that
each member states of SADC should urge industrialists to
strengthen testing of their products and made them realized that
quality is essential to the very existence of businesses. They
also agreed that monitoring and control authorities should work
together with companies to improve quality of local products.
</P>
<P>
SADC started implementing its plan on standardization and
quality control in 1985 and it holds annual meeting on the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
