<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls on Parties Concerned to Break Deadlock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Concluding his first Middle
East tour on Wednesday, the United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan called on all the parties concerned to take hard decisions
to break the deadlock in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Summing up his trip at a news conference held here, Annan said
he was encouraged by the fact that Israeli and Arab leaders he has
met have all expressed "a deep desire for peace" despite the
impasse in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"There is disagreement as to the reason for the current
impasse. The Arab leaders I have met in the region have been
deeply skeptical about the good faith of the current Israeli
government ..., at the same time, they reiterated their support
for a just and comprehensive peace with Israel," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, he noted that Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and the Israeli government have complained the
Palestinians for "not fully committed to the fight against
terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Before his visit here, Annan has traveled to Jordan, Egypt,
Lebanon, Syria and the Palestinian self-rule area to hold
discussions on exploring ways of breaking the stalemate in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
But he has played down any expectation for a breakthrough
through the efforts made in his mission, saying he only came to
the region to "learn, to see and to encourage" the parties to keep
faith toward peace.
</P>
<P>
"It seems to me very important that the current impasse in the
peace process should be broken. I call on all concerned to show
the courage, wisdom and vision to take the hard decisions that
will be necessary," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
He said that progress should be made on all tracks of the
Middle East peace process, especially the resumption of the
stalled Israeli-Syrian peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"I am of the opinion that without peace with Syria, there can
be no comprehensive peace in the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between Israel and Syria came to a halt nearly
two years ago over the future of the Golan Heights, a piece of
Syrian land captured by Israel in the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
Annan expressed deep concern about the deadlock in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process due to Israel's expansion of
settlements, and continuing closure of Palestinian self-rule areas
that aggravates the economic hardship of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the Oslo accords must be implemented and the
relevant U.N. resolutions, based on the land-for-peace principle,
be fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
"We are engaged in a process that will either move forward or
backwards, but that cannot for long remain stalled," he warned.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said he particularly discussed with Israeli
leaders the implementation of the U.N. Security Council Resolution
425 that calls for an unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel has offered to withdraw from south Lebanon if the
Lebanese government agrees to an arrangement concerning the
security of the bordering areas.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has rejected the proposal, maintaining that Israel's
offer is not in compliance with the U.N. Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Israeli-U.N. relations that are always at
odds due to Israel's refusal to implement the relevant U.N.
resolutions, Annan said he would try to improve the ties and
normalize Israel's status in the world organization.
</P>
<P>
Israel is the only member state excluded from the U.N. regional
groups. This means it has no chance of being elected to serve on
main organs, such as the Security Council or the Economic and
Social Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980326.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-26 </DATE_TIME>
